VGreat headphones (with a few minor annoyances)
p41
sg5
VThese headphones are excellent. After listening to music with mediocre headphones for the last few years, the RS 180 opened up a whole new level of details to my music. I'm impressed by the clarity and 'crispness' of the sound and good reproduction of lower frequencies.Pros:- excellent sound quality- comfortable to wear even for an extended time- electronic noise almost not noticeable, no 'hiss'- easy to set up and useCons:- may interfere with wireless network- power button on base station difficult to operate with one hand.- usable range in realistic living environment significantly smaller than advertised, idealistic range- small delay may be a problem when using as hearing aide for TV- noise threshold causes cut offs during very quiet partsLong review:The headphones are light and comfortable to wear even after several hours. In fact, I would forget that I'm wearing headphones if it wasn't for the music. Thanks to the digital transmission there is no static noise and the electronic noise is almost unnoticeable. The sound quality is great and can compete with high-quality wired headphones. The unit is easy to set up and can be operated with normal batteries or rechargeable batteries. Rechargeable batteries are charged when the headphones are placed on the base station. I like that the unit includes several useful accessories: the power supply comes with country adapters, the main audio connection cable has decent length (2m), there is a 3.5mm jack socket to 6.3mm jack plug adapter and a 3.5mm jack socket to 2 RCA adapter. A cable mount and binder help to install all the cables neatly. The RS 180 base unit also has RCA outputs. In this way it can be integrated into an already existing connection between a sound source and an amplifier.The overall good impression is impaired by a number of minor problems, though:The KLEER technology for digital transmission promises to work without interfering with other wireless devices, such as wireless phones and wireless networks. However, I observe interference of the headphones with my wireless network: one of my computer loses the wireless internet connection occasionally. Sometimes it would work for several hours without problems, sometimes the connection dropped out every few minutes. Everytime the connection was re-established as soon as I switched off the RS 180 base station, so there is a clear link. This happened when the base station was located close to the computer. After I relocated the RS 180 base station to the other side of the room the situation got much better. So far, I haven't encountered any more drop-outs. I also noticed a negative impact on the speed of my wireless network if the RS 180 base station is located near a computer. In my experience one has to separate the RS 180 base station as far as possible from a wireless computer network. Note that I never noticed any interference effect on the RS 180 headphones.Transmission from the base station to the headset seems to require the input signal amplitude to pass a certain, small threshold. As a consequence, transmission cuts in and out during an extremely quiet part of music. It is therefore a good idea to follow the suggestion in the manual to turn up the volume of the input device as much as possible (but avoiding distortions) and to regulate the volume directly on the headphones.The range within my apartment building is about 70 ft before the connection brakes up (the Sennheiser web page declares a rage of up 100 m = 328 ft line of sight). The usable range certainly depends a lot on the specifics of the building and I can move around anywhere within my apartment without transmission problems.Both the base station and the headphone are easy to operate. It may take a little time to get used to the buttons on the headphones while wearing them as they are not easy to distinguish by 'the feel'. The only real complaint I have is that switching the base station on or off requires two hands: one for pushing the power button and the other one for keeping the base station in place. It would be better if the base station could be powered with just one hand.A general feature of wireless headphones appears to be a tiny delay in the signal. This is only a problem if the headphones are used as a hearing aide when watching TV, for example. If the headphones are used in parallel with the TV speakers I notice a small delay in the audio coming from the headphones. It's tiny but noticeable and causes an echo-like effect. However, I'm not using the headphones as a hearing aide so it's not a concern for me.The RS 180 has an open design so that outside noise is not suppressed. This is a design feature, not a disadvantage and results in a more natural sound reproduction. But if environment noise is a concern then the closed systems RS 170 and RS 160 may be a better choice.In summary, I can recommend these headphones because of the high audio quality and ease of wearing. The problems I encountered could either be resolved (interference) or are only minor annoyances to me and are outbalanced by the superb sound experience.
