sg3
VSennheiser RS 180
p69
sg5
VOk first the particulars.  The evaluation system consisted of the following:  Sony STR-DA5200ES, Sony (Costco) BDP-BX57, Sony CDP-CX335.  The Blu-ray player was connected via HDMI & the 400 Cd Mega-changer was hooked up via analog connects. SACD were demoed both as 2-channel & Multi-channel.The initial impression with the RS 180's is their extreme musicality.  That is to say every note was rendered as a distinct & succint item.  Next, is the warm sound.  If you want headphones that are strident, then look elsewhere. I started off with a SACD (Super Audio CD) sampler from Concord Jazz (Volume 2).  Track 2 of this disc is one that I am quite familiar with as I also have the complete SACD where this song came from.  That song being the wonderful Nature Boy by Nnenna Freelon.  I know this is cliched, but I literally heard notes that I never heard before.  The headphones presented a very wide soundstage with ample presence but not too much "air".  As I stated above these are very warm sounding headphones.  This was, no doubt, influenced by the headphone amp of my 5200ES.  You would think a $1500.00 dollar receiver could do better, but alas that is a nit that I shall pick another day. It is easy to use these cans for long periods of time as the ear pieces are comfortable & compliant.  Listening to the very forward & lively CD, Greatest Hits by Duran Duran instantly transported me back to 1984 (17 is teh best age, evah!) as I reveled in the amazing musicmanship of the band.  I had forgotten just how good (& well produced) these guys were.  Next to Frankie Goes to Hollywood, I don't think another pop act captures the zeitgeist of the 80's as well.Next I moved on to a Blu ray concert of Hall & Oates Live at the Troubadour.  This is were the warm fuzzies of these headphones really paid off.  In this casual close-miked setting I felt as if I was actually there & had to resist the urge several times to turn around & "see" the rest of the crowd.  I should note that while I was listening to this selection I was moving around my approx. 1100 sq foot apartment with no loss of fidelity at all.  I finally ended up with the Blu ray of Transformers.  Now again I have to mention that my Sony receiver was found lacking.  Since it cannot process the lossless codecs via bitstream, everything was fed to it as PCM.  This caused the receiver to automatically apply its own processing (aptly named Headphone 2CH).  In a word I did not like it.  You could tell it was trying to distill the 5.1 mixes down to 2 channels & frankly it did not do a good job.  Voices were diffused & effects were too front & center.  Also, I had to play with my receiver volume & the headphone volumes several times through my listening today.  This was entirely the fault of the Sony.  Having said that, the sheer ability of this set to reproduce sound simply overcame the shortcomings.Setup was fairly easy as there is an ikea like pictogram (with words in several languages) that show/tell you how to get started.  First charge is supposed to be 16 hours, I let them go roughly 24 hours.  Others have mentioned that the controls on the right earpiece take a little to get used to.  Maybe it was the forewarnings, but I had no trouble.  The headphones are light & I hardly noticed that they were, in fact, on my head.  I like that the charging station gives them a "home" to go to.In a word, the Sennheiser RS 180 remote headphones are just about perfect.  I did not give them 5 stars across the board, because I feel that they are about 2 tenths away from that.  The high end could be just a tad more broad, the soundstage is (IMHO) too wide, but for less than 300 bucks, you could not do better.
