VI bought two RS180's headphones to replace RS120 I used for years. The sound of RS180 is definitely superior to RS120.  But the range is 20-30 ft at best (in direct view!) so that it's pretty much impossible to move around the house without loosing the signal. The signal drops when I go to the backyard, 15 ft away from the transmitter through a glass door (still in direct view). RS120 had strong reception in all these spots.The worst: I use 2 headsets with one transmitter station, RS180 system is self-tuning that is you don't manually tune the frequency, it does it for you. This sounds like a nice feature, as you should not manually tune the headphones any more. But if one headset looses the signal, the transmitter station starts searching for the signal to self-tune and THIS knocks off frequency the second headset!! That is, signal drops in both headsets at the same time even though one of them is in the range. With the clear operation range of only 20-30 ft it make the RS180 pretty useless for me.To the manufacturer: the claim was that 2.4GHz was supposed to boost the range without interference, but it not even close to RS120 running at 926MHz
