VGood but the controls are a step backwards
p108
sg5
VThis is my third set of Sennheiser wireless headphones. These are the first I've tried with the digital "Kleer" transmission, and it really does reduce the hiss and static compared to my previous RS 130 set.  Comfort, range and sound quality exceed my expectations.My main complaint is the controls, which are much harder to operate than the ones on the RS 130.  The volume is controlled by two little buttons that you have to feel for -- if you're adjusting the volume without taking them off, as most people will want to.  (Even taking the headset off to look at the buttons won't help if you're listening in the dark, as I like to do sometimes.)  There are actually three buttons in a row, and the one in between vol+ and vol- is the on/off button, so if you try for say vol+ and miss, you turn the headset off. This seems completely stupid to me, sorry if that seems harsh, but the controls were so much more copacetic on the older, cheaper headset.  The RS 130 volume control was a wheel, like a scroll wheel on a mouse.  Intuitive, and impossible to get it confused with anything else.I also dislike having to turn the base unit on, then turn the headset on, every time I put them on.  The old 130s would turn off when I hung them on the base/charger, and turn on automagically when I lifted them off and put them on.  The On button on the RS 180 base is stupidly designed also: When I push it, the base just slides out of the way, unless I hold the base unit down while pressing.  All they would have had to do is put the button on top, so you press down, and then the base wouldn't slide away from you when you press it.  Or better yet, just have it turn itself on when it detects sound input, like the old 130s did. I shouldn't have to touch the On button at all.I took one star off for these dumb design decisions.  If my nitpicks don't sound like they'll be an issue for you, then buy 'em and enjoy.
