VHad been very disappointed with 3 Sennheiser previous lower-end models of cordless phones, so I tried their top of the line digital RS180.  Initially I was blown away by the best sound I have ever heard from cordless phones -- as I sat in one position in a chair near the base station and listened to an entire CD.  Unit seemed to have good workmanship, fit well and comfortably on my head.  But when I had the nerve to try listening to music while standing and moving about the room, sound was only heard in short bursts of static and music with dead silence most of the time.  Every move of my head or body killed the sound.  Turning on any appliance (vacuum, microwave, et al.) killed all sound.  I even tried turning off my computer's Router (2.4 MHz) at the other end of the house, but no improvement in the headphones' performance.  Once I got more than 12 feet from the transmitter, there was no sound at all other than the occasional brief burst of static.  I had planned on listening while working around my house, a small one-level in the AZ desert, but this was fully impossible.  After 3 weeks of trying everything I could think of to make them work better, they were returned to Amazon for a refund.  I am now happily using  Brookstone analog cordless phones, and the sound is clear, loud, and steady all over my house and immediate yard.  The sound is quite good though not the superb performance of the Sennheiser (on the rare occasions when they worked), and the fit and comfort are not fully up to Sennheiser.  Plus a drawback: my 2.4 GHz router does have to be turned OFF or the Brookstone phones do not work well, but I can live with that limitation.  Definitely, the Sennheiser name (once a proud brand) is off my list of acceptable brands I might purchase in the future.  ---LarryKJ, Wickenburg, AZ
