VGood, but be aware if you like solo instrument music
p131
sg5
VI've owned these cans for a month now, and I can say this headphone is not bad. I listen to classical music mostly (90%) along with a bit of rock music and others (10%).To me, it took about 20 hours of listening to break in. At the beginning, brass and voice especially sounded rather recessed and dull. But now they sound upfront as they should. Also, the cans sounded too mellow at first, but they sound much more neutral now. It is still rather on the "warm" side, but I would say only to a pleasant degree to my ears.To be specific.... Sound staging is quite good. Bass is full, prompt, and accurate. Range is rather limited, but I was going to use them indoors mostly anyways, so it is not a big deal. Control keys on the headphone is not really well designed as many reviews pointed out, but i can live with it. Convenience factor of a wireless headphone is a huge plus.Then...Why only 3 stars?The main problem that bothers me is the presence of "noise" especially when listening to solo instrument music. Even at a not-so-high volume, quite audible noises kick in when a piano player playing piano sonata, for example, hits keys strong enough. What happens if you raise volume further?? You hear severely distorted sound (or "clipping").(However, for other genre of music where many instruments play simultaneously, RS180 doesn't show a similar issue and it is usually my ears, not the headphones, that cannot take any more before clipping kicks in.)I am no expert, but here is my guess for the issue.Your music is sum of all sound waves at different frequencies. When you listen to a symphony, you typically have a wide range of frequencies going from ~20Hz to ~20kHz. But when you listen to piano sonata, you have narrow peaks at a few frequencies in the sound spectrum at any given time. At a similar volume level recognized by your ears for these two different kinds of music, there should be much larger wave amplitudes to be delivered by your headphones in the single instrument case compared to symphony.The "KLEER" wireless transmission should have a certain threshold for "clipping" for any narrow frequency range. The problem, I believe, is that this threshold is set rather low either due to technological limit or for safety reasons, and this limit leads to sound distortion at a not-so-high volume when you listen to solo instruments. (I don't think the clipping comes from the diaphragm itself, because my other Sennheiser headphones handle similar volume levels without a sweat.)To exclude the possibility that other parts of my system is causing the problem, let me point out that my RS180 is plugged into an amplifier (Rotel) capable of handling lots of amps of currents. I tried various combination of volume levels on the headphone and on my amp, but I couldn't resolve the issue. I talked to a Sennheiser rep to get around the issue, but I figured that they don't have solutions to this either.... And yes, the transmitter is set at -8dB.Despite the problem, I didn't return these cans because they do their job for most other genre of music. Again, convenience of a wireless headphone (and decent sound when it works) certainly secures its spot in my man cave. But still, I should go back to my good old, "wired" cans when I listen to single instruments. Hope Sennheiser comes with better wireless cans next time.
