VFlawed user interface
p136
sg5
VSound quality is great for these headphones.I have two problems with the HDR 180:1) The placement and size of the buttons on the headphones to turn them on and off and adjust volume and balance is terrible.  The buttons are tiny and placed very close together.  The only way to do anything, whether it be to turn them on or off, adjust the volume or adjust the balance is to take them off, turn on lights if necessary, and watch what you're doing.  I'm a person who can pretty much do everything on a TV remote in the dark by touch.  With these headphones, I can do nothing by touch.  The most important button, the on-off, is between the buttons to change the volume.  It should have been off by itself.  All the buttons are more or less flush with the surrounding case and this makes the problem worse.  In the end, the only way to change anything is to take them off, turn the light on and watch while you press the proper button, which on the face of it seems silly.  I have big fingers and that makes all of this much worse, given the minuscule size of the buttons.2) Previous versions (RS140 for example) turned themselves off when they did not get a signal for a while.  That meant that you walk away from them and they would shut themselves off, saving precious battery life.  The HDR 180 shuts off the sending unit, but not the headphones when the signal stops, for example when the sleep timer on the TV shuts it off.  That means that you have to physically walk to the base station to turn it on to resume.  The RS 140 stayed in some sort of sleep mode and came on when the signal from the TV returned.  The headphones themselves, by contrast, have to be turned off manually.  Given the tiny buttons, that means turning lights on to do it.  This is the exact reverse of the way the RS 140's worked and the previous method was far superior in daily use.Again, I like the sound, but hate the interface.
