VSuperb headset with some minor shortcomings
p158
sg5
VI have owned these Sennheiser RS180 headphones for about a month (bought them elsewhere from a reputed online dealer) and am completely satisfied with them. My positive and negative experiences are listed below.1. Crystal Clear, Great Frequency Response, Wireless Works Great -- After about 50 hrs of breaking-in, they really open up and shine. They are very airy (typical of expensive open-air designs), bass is very balanced (not booming), and extremely good frequency response all the way up as far as I can hear. I can even pick up nuances in some tracks that I hadn't heard before. These are good for extended listening periods since they don't fatigue the ears due to the lack of boominess. Bass heads will be disappointed, but all other music lovers will definitely love these. The earpads are super comfortable too, and these headphones are super-light - almost all plastic, but they seem to be OK in fit and finish and will probably last a decade unless I walk over them several times. The digital transmission system from Kleer is almost flawless, but you will probably get half the range they claim. If I move 3 rooms (3 walls in-between), I get occasional sound drop-outs (about 1 sec) but no loud buzzing or shrill sounds. But that's not a big problem.2. Setup - I had some problem with interference when I first set them up; the transmitter and receiver would lose sync frequently). But after moving them about 3 feet away from my other wi-fi equipment, the problem seems to have gone away. The cords provided are long enough (5-6ft) long to allow placement adjustments. I have tested the RS180 with my HK DPR 2005 receiver, with a Squeezebox v3, an HD TV and a Blu-Ray player, all in different rooms. Seems to work just fine. You don't have to fiddle at all to get them to work. It took me a while to realize that the power led on the transmitter is also the power button. Once you power up both the transmitter and the headphones, it takes less than 5 seconds to sync and begin listening.3. There is a slight delay about 100 ms (in my unscientific estimation) due to the pre-processing/transmission-reception/post-processing. Not enough to cause any noticeable video-audio sync issues - I looked hard, and couldn't see any sync problems. But, if you turn on the TV speakers and use the headset as well, there is definitely an echo effect due to the headset's lag. However, if you turn down the TV volume to a somewhat low level (or turn up the headset volume) so that the headset "overpowers" the TV speakers, the echo effect diminishes greatly. But for general listening from your stereo, or late night TV/BluRay/DVD watching, the quality is superb. There are no sound drop-outs within the same or adjacent rooms. But, of course, since these open-air cans, they will leak some sound. So, that is not acceptable, you need to look at the RS160 or the RS170 closed cans - but remember that those will have slightly different sound quality.4. The supplied rechargeable batteries seem to last 16-18 hours on a charge, which is very good. Best of all, these are standard AAA size, so when these die, you won't have to hunt for expensive proprietary batteries. A big plus!5. The only shortcoming (and for this, the product gets a star deducted) is that there is no optical input to the transmitter! All devices nowadays have digital line outputs. The transmission itself is digital, so it is strange that there is no provision to accept a digital signal as input to the transmitter. Perhaps, it's a cost-cutting decision?
