VFits *ALL* my criteria for great headphones
p168
sg5
VI have/had both multiple wired/wireless headphones, so I've put together a mental list over time, of what worked, and what hasn't.  These headphones were meant to be multi-purpose: music, primarily classical, New Age, contemporary (a wide range), as well as T.V. (connected to the stereo). This is what I found:Positive:1. Charging is pain free... just drop the phones on the base unit, and they not only easily find their own center, but charge very quickly.2. Range.  There is nowhere I can go in my home (3-stories, 3500 sq. ft.) where I can make it drop out, or even produce any noise/static, including down my driveway to my mailbox. Range is fabulous.3. Sound.  Excellent. Best I've had in a headphone.4. Comfort.  This is a complaint I've had in other headphones, that either didn't have enough padding in the headband, or the earcups, or were not adjustable enough, too tight, etc.  The RS 180 resolves all that.  Perfectly surrounds your ears (as opposed to 'open-air' which press against your ears), and the headband is thickly padded.  The phones are adjustable, hold their adjustment, and apply the perfect amount of pressure to create a soft "seal" without cutting off your circulation.Negative:1. While the controls are very versatile (balance, on-off, mute, volume), I would have liked the on-off/mute button a little more pronounced, or separate from the other row of buttons... perhaps on the other earcup.  However, a small nit, that in no way puts a dent in a fantastic product.2. Pricey.  It's an excellent, well-designed, quality product.  You should expect to pay the price, unless you want to sacrifice/cut corners.
