VFirst, let me say that I don't really consider myself a "die-hard" audiophile, that said, besides owning these rs180 wireless phones, I also own Sennheiser hd-555, hd-598, and the hd-650 corded cans.  I appreciate solid performing headphones and the rs180's fill that need exceptionally well and have the big added benefit of being cordless.  I'm not going to go into a full sound quality breakdown here, but I will say for those familiar with the 598's and 650's, the RS180's IMHO fall somewhere between the two.  Closer to the 598's I think.  A little better mids and bass than the 598's.  Brighter, airier, but not quite the very fine overall perfomance of the 650's in regards to soundstaging and imaging. Although, I do think they work better than the hd 650's for movie watching.  But not with music.  This really is an incredible achievment for a wireless headset.Set up was as simple as it gets.  I tried connecting through both the headphone jack and also the zone2 outs on my pioneer vsx-819h (used for home theater).  There was really not a noticable difference in the quality of sound between the two connections, so I decided to stay with the phone jack for ease of use.  Charging the headset took about 8 hours.  Once charged I was able to stroll out into my back yard (150ft) with no signal loss at all.  I also haven't experienced any problems with my wireless network as described in some other reviews that I've read.  I found the headset to be light and comfortable (a bit heavier than the hd555's they will replace for movie watching) and have worn them for up to four hours so far with no sense of fatigue or any other difficulties.  I also connected them to my Denon AVR-3312CI (used for music) and found them to be very competant for music appreciation.  Though as stated above, they won't be replacing my hd-650's for this purpose.  I would also add that so far I haven't experienced any drop outs or noticible back ground noise at all.  I've been very impressive.As for the controls, yes it's a bit of a bother having to turn both the base and headset on before use.  And yes, the controls on the headset take a little getting used to.  However, I find both issues to be very minor and believe the perfomance of these phones far out-weighs the few negatives.Overall, I would most definitely recommend these to anyone looking for solid performing wireless headphones.
