sg3
VThe sound "seal" doesn't, plus two other faults. Still excellent.
p186
sg5
VThese headphones are excellent in every regard except three.  First, the seal that is to keep the sound from leaking into the room is not much of a seal at all:  My wife can hear the dialog when I'm watching TV using the headphones.  The sound is, of course, at greatly reduced volume, but just loud enough to be annoying. Unfortunately, Sennheiser offers no alternate ear pads for the easily-replaceable open-foam ones supplied. It could have and should be doing so. That doesn't mean they shouldn't also supply the ones they are: The advantage to the supplied ear pads is that, when you pause the sound, you can hear people in the room speak without taking off the earphones.  And they let in enough fresh air so your ears don't heat up, as happens with denser ear pads.Second, the controls were designed by an incompetent.  In order to hear anything, you have to not only turn the headphones themselves on, but the charging/transmitting tower as well.  The tower should blow through 2 cents worth of electricity per year and "listen" for headphones to request it to power-up.  What's worse, the switch on the tower is located in a place that requires you to grasp the tower with one hand while pressing the on switch with the other. Otherwise, it just slides away from you across the table.  Really, really bad design.  But the headphones are worse:  All five controls, the three you actually use and the two you never use, are all lined up together in a perfect row just below your right ear where you can neither see them nor feel them with the headphones in place.  Except one of the five, the one you actually can see because you use it to turn the headphones on before you plunk them on your head, has a just barely raised logo of some sort on it.  This string of five-in-a-row buttons makes trying to change the volume maddeningly difficult.  Essentially, you find a volume you can live with, and you live with it.Finally, and I can hardly fault Sennheiser for this, the RS 180s lose when they go up in battle with my microwave oven, cutting in and out as long as I'm within six feet of the oven.  What's remarkable is that I've never owned a pair of wireless headphones before that could even approach the kitchen before transitioning into white noise, the transmitter being 30 feet away in the living room through two walls, so the fact that the Sennheiser headphones work perfectly in the kitchen and beyond, save when the oven is actively turning, is quite remarkable. The way to have address this would have been to decouple where the headphones have to be vs. where the transmitter has to be, but since they put transmitter and charger together, then insisted that the transmitter be separately powered up, they precluded the possibility of putting each device in the best place.Now, all this may sound really, really bad, but in spite of these negatives, these are the first wireless headphones I've ever elected to actually keep. Other reviewers have talked about the good stuff, and the good stuff adds up to the full four stars I've given them. And I've come up with solutions to the last two problems I can live with: The tower I've velcroed to my side table (I'm hoping my wife doesn't read this) so I can turn on the transmitter with one hand. I've touched the up and down volume controls with a hot soldering iron to to make them so that I can feel them (the DOWN is sufficiently rough to stand out, and the UP ended up with a round blob of old solder melted into it--both easily discernible), and I have a remote in the kitchen that will let me pause the TV while I cook something in the microwave while I'm under the headphones. Now, if I can just address problem one by dampening my wife's hearing a bit by maybe injecting a little caulk in her ears while she's asleep... Well, perhaps not.
