VPricey, but mostly good...  Range issues..
p191
sg5
VI bought these for work (at home.)  I wanted something wireless, of decent quality with good range.  Setup was quick and easy.  The base station charges the headphones when you place them on top, which I do at the end of the day.  They play fine all throughout the day so they are full charged each morning.  When you take the headphones off, you must press the ON button on the base unit, then press the power button on the headphones before they will work.  The buttons on the headphone are definitely hard to discern without looking at them (ie, while wearing them.)  You can feel the power button, it has some raised edging, but it's rather thin and small - the volume up button is above that, but it's a little clumsy.  I would have designed it with a little knob to press for power on/off and turn of volume up/down.  That would have been so much nicer and easier- especially when you need to quickly adjust the volume to, say, answer a phone or talk to someone.  The way it is, you have to pop them off using both hands (so no holding a phone), and press the on/off button, or click and hold the volume down button, or otherwise adjust the volume from the source (computer, stereo or whatever the base station is getting it's audio from.)I like the "around the ear" design, I find it more comfortable.  These are perfectly comfortable for extended periods; though I find I usually never have them on for more than a couple hours.  Sometimes I just let them hang around my neck instead of putting them down; convenient.My biggest gripe is the range.  Advertised 320', which is quite a long ways.  My mailbox is about 60 feet away and the headphones start cutting out- though the signal IS going through a layer of brick.  Also it cuts out inside my house, at only 30 feet or so, if I am in the kitchen.  But, to be fair, there are a couple walls and partially a refridgerator between the headphones and the transmitter.  I can listen to them upstairs, the signal going through the floor, no problem.  I will experiment with them soon and update this review.  I will move the transmitter just outside and test unobstructed line-of-sight range and also move it to a higher spot- above my bookshelf; right now it's about a foot off the floor next to my computer.  Conclusion: Range can severly suffer if you start walking around corners or have too much between the headphones and the transmitter.  Inside the house I get about 30 to 40 feet before it starts cutting out.  House was built in the 70's and there's not a lot of internal wall insulation.  I'd like to be able to sit in my screened porch and listen, but it cuts out just before I get to the door, which is no more than 50' from the transmitter.  Arg. We'll see if moving the transmitter (use a long audio extension cable) helps any.These are pretty expensive headphones, I had expected to be able to go anywhere in my house (including the porch) and get a good signal, but that hasn't been the case.  I don't know of any good alternatives, though, so I'll keep these and experiment with moving the transmitter so that I can get a better signal in other parts of the house. (It's not a large house, about 2400sq/ft.)  My wireless phones can reach everywhere, why not a pair of $300 headphones?
