VGreat headphones; small annoyances. Wireless is closing the gap on wired, but nowhere near 1:1 yet.
p203
sg5
VLet me start off this review by saying that if you need a huge rundown on the specifics of these particular headphones, you're better off just searching for video reviews on YouTube since they go into great detail on every aspect of the product. I'll be as brief as possible listing the annoyances I had with the RS 180's, but I will say right off the bat having owned the RS 120 II & RS 170 from Sennheiser - these definitely are more comfortable and way better sounding (at least to the RS 120 II).At the end of the day I really want to emphasize that I do like these headphones a lot, but there are some things that you may find annoying about them as I do. I've listed them below in no particular order.AC adapter has short cabling and is on the thin side. Ideal for traveling, but less so for home setups.Automatic shut off after 5 minutes of no audio signal. Would have been nice to be able to toggle this feature; since I like "always on" setups.Requires pressing of the power button on the transmitter to wake from standby instead of automatically when an audio signal is detected.Flimsy plastic tabs on ear muffs can easily be broken with gentle force. Most complaints about the RS 180 is regarding this.Power on/off button is located right between volume up and down buttons (On headphones). Very easy to accidentally press when adjusting volume.As far as everything else goes - I couldn't be happier. Sound quality is leaps and bounds better than the RS 120 II's and ANY Bluetooth set I've tried. Slightly better than the RS 170's as well. Still nowhere near the quality of a wired headset in terms of full range sound, but this is the best offering we can get for now and I'm grateful for it. If you have questions, feel free to ask in comments.
