VExtremely comfortable, with great sound quality
p209
sg5
VI've got these headphones around Jan 5, 2011. These are my first pair of over the ear headphones (i've used IEMS and earbuds before) and first wireless headphones. I wanted wireless headphones with good battery life, sound quality, and comfort. I use these headphones for music, movies, and gaming.Sound: These are the best headphones I've ever heard, though all my past headphones were <$20 so that isn't a very helpful is it? Despite not having a trained ear, I'll try describing the audio as best as possible. I found that the bass had a decent punch, and was very clean. Past headphones I've used tend to have a muddy/blurry bass compared with the RS180. While all genres sounded better than I have ever heard on a headphone, I found orchestra music to benefit the most from these.edit: the "ssssh" sound was due to my poor source. Male sure to check your/source.I found that there seems to be a slight "ssssssh" sound when the headphone volume is less than 4 clicks from the max. One can eliminate this problem by leaving the headphone volume at 4 or more clicks below the max, and instead changing the volume from the source. These headphones aren't as loud as others, but they play loud enough just to be slightly uncomfortable rather than ear deafening loud which is nice. You just need to get used to raising the volume higher than you normally would with other headphones. Of course since these are open headphones you get sound leakage. The leakage is about as loud as a pair of desktop speakers at a semi-low volume. If the big transmitter wasn't a hint enough, it is obvious that these headphones should only be used at home for private listening.Design: I love how the transmitter also works as a stand/charger. I just wish that you could connect it to two different sources at once; I have to unplug the cable from the transmitter when I'm switching from my PC to my TV. I think the volume button issue is a bit overblown. I found it very easy to use, since the power/mute button which is slightly beveled, is actually between the Vol + and Vol - buttons. So I just have to slide my finger from the Vol + button down to the Vol - button if I want to lower the volume. It took me literally less than 5 minutes to get used to this. The headphones are extremely comfortable. They literally feel like pillows because none of the plastic has contact with your head; the plush velour pads are the only things resting on your head. Velour pads can be removed by turning them counter clockwise. They attract dust but can easily be cleaned by rubbing both pads together and blowing away the dust with a hair dryer or low powered vacuum.Range: I honesty only needed these to work within the vicinity of my room but the RS180 had signal within my entire house (even the garage) which is excellent. Though when I went near the kitchen the signal would cut out when I moved or touched my headphones; that however is to be expected with most wireless devices.Build Quality: While good, the materials feel slightly cheap for this price point. While the build quality is definitely not poor, the headphone feels more like a $50-60 headphone rather than a $250 headphone. The plastic though is of good quality, and the gloss surprisingly looks nice while being scratch and finger print resistant. You cant see in the photos but there is a sparkle to the paint job which looks nice. The velour quality of the pads is excellent and is very soft and comfy.Battery Life: The battery life is supposed to be 24 hours which I highly doubt, but even then I don't expect battery life to be an issue at all. I forgot that these even ran on batteries. I wear them every day and place them on the charger when I'm not using them. Never had the battery die on me, but the fact that it takes regular AAA Nimh rechargeable batteries means you can easily replace them if they ever die.Overall: These headphones met my every need. The reason that the RS180 is not perfect is because of the "ssssh" sound volume is less than 4 clicks from the max (can easily be fixed by adjusting source volume and even then it isn't that big of a deal and most would probably not notice it), the build quality for the price you're paying, and the lack of another headphone jack on the transmitter (most probably don't care about this). They retail for $300 but I suggest you get these for $250 or lower as $300 is a bit overpriced for the build quality.
