VRS180 versus RS140/RS130
p215
sg5
VWe have three of the older analog Sennheiser wireless headphones (one RS140 - it failed recently after 5 years and two RS130s). The RS180 has zero hiss/pops/static whereas the older units have had these at times.  The bass has been punched up as others have noted, so these do not give high fidelity sound - I am using a home entertainment system amplifier and can adjust for this. I have had no problem getting good reception around our Garrison type house, where as I have AT TIMES with the older RS140 and RS130 analog units; when I go into the garage or outside the house (we have an aluminum covering on our wall insulation) reception becomes a problem, even at 50 ft from the transmitter. Standing within two feet of our running microwave cuts off all sound from the headphones; the sound returns when I retreat 4 to 5 feet away. The one feature that has caused me much trouble is the new method of adjusting sound and turning the headphones on and off. I find it hard to believe Sennheiser did any Beta testing of these headphones in a population with large fingers or toughened finger skin or abraded finger skin. One needs supple, sensitive finger tips to quickly discriminate the buttons and I doubt this applies to most people over 40 and to people who work with their hands a lot! Except for this serious design flaw I would have rated it 5 stars.  They are comfortable, and give clean good sound when the bass is adjusted.  Those wanting a more booming bass are no doubt the target market and they will love the sound as is.
