VMost of the negatives mentioned on other reviews are pretty accurate - the controls are way too tiny so other than the up volume button you need to take them off to avoid hitting the wrong button.  Having to turn on the base station every time is also a big negative.  I haven't seen what I consider the biggest negative mentioned previously though - if I plug them into the analog out on my receiver, I cannot listen to any digital (I.e., HDMI) sources - so no Apple TV, Blu-ray/CD player, etc.  I suppose I could run a separate set of analog cables to every source from my receiver (some, like the Apple TV don't have analog outputs though...), but that's just ridiculous.  The other option (and the one I am doing currently) is to plug the base station in to the headphone jack when I want to listen through the headphones...somehow not as slick as I was expecting "wireless" to be.The sound quality is pretty good, no problem with wireless interference at all.  The bass response is pretty weak however, but I can't fault them for that as it is pretty well documented that the bass is not stellar.All in all they aren't bad, but I think I will go back to wired headphones.  The negatives for these just outweigh the positives IMO.
