VBest headphone set I've ever owned
p287
sg5
VI am sure I have not even explored all this headphone set can do. The sound quality is crisp and clear; the stereo sound is almost a surround sound--sometimes I've had to check whether a sound I heard in the "background" was coming from the phones or from my brick-and-mortar surroundings (and so far it has always turned out it came from the phones). The automatic level control is nice especially when watching TV; that feature does make a difference, so if you want to preserve dynamic contrast, e.g., when listening to classical music, leave it off.The ergonomics of this headphone set are nothing short of superb; it adjusts snugly to the shape of your head, fits comfortably around your ears, and stays put as you move, without ever putting too much pressure on. Only the volume and balance controls took me a little while to get used to; sometimes I would accidentally turn off the phones rather than adjust the volume. And when you first plug it into the stereo (turning off the speakers), a few seconds may pass until the sound is played through the headphones, leaving you in the mute during that time; therefore, you might want to not switch from speakers to phones during key dialogue or so.Previous reviewers have remarked on the slight delay in sound transmission; I'll say it is about one-tenth to one-fifth of a second. That I can live with when watching TV, and it certainly is "same difference" when consuming audio-only sources.Brief dropouts can occur when my microwave oven is on and I happen to pass within 2' of it. But I haven't had the experience of the headphone transmitter signal and the wireless Internet signal interfering with each other: the transmitter sits about 3' away from the wireless router, and I sometimes wear the phones while sitting at the computer. The two wireless signals seem to work just fine at the same time.
