VIf you LISTEN to music, I think you will like what you hear
p309
sg5
VWhy did I wait so long to buy these?  I have been listening to a very enjoyable set of Sony cans for about 15 years, but the replacement ear pads are now falling off from extended use.  The Sony cans were VERY comfortable, but a bit heavy because component integration back then was not what it is today.  Another problem that has been becoming more troublesome is because wireless headphones in that era used the 900 MHz band and that continues to make them more susceptible to interference. I am old enough that I still have 4 good-quality Reel to Reel tape decks, 4 turntables including a Dual Golden 1 that I bought new in the previous millennium, and a slew of discrete components that can feed me a great signal.  I will concede that I do little casual listening to something in the background while I work. I much prefer to listen to a wide range of jazz, classical, and popular music - closely, and as the main focus of what I am doing. I feel I have a good basis for judging the quality of my recordings, whether they are a seldom played 1970's Quadraphonic vinyl DG recording of the Boston Pops coming over my living room system vs. the same recording digitized and coming from my PC.  Is there a difference? Definitely.  Enough of a difference that I am willing to lug around a couple of tons of media, components, and wiring when I want to listen somewhere else?  Not a chance.Thanks to the RS 180's, I am pleasantly rediscovering my music collection with every new listening session - be it 100% analog or the digital version I can fit on a two terabyte drive in my pocket.  With very gently applied adjustments from a software plug-in called the DFX Audio Enhancer, I find I can re-experience the sound stage, imaging, and frequency profile I remember from before the time (last 5 years) my listening was restricted by living in an apartment! Either way, good electronics all the way is a must.  Purists will say using any "signal enhancer" is bad, and I totally agree - IF your listening room is Symphony Hall or some other first rate venue.  But after a now long ago decade as a high end audio salesman (after several years at Radio Shack helped me earn my electrical engineering degree), I still say the best sound is what YOU like best, and if you start with a great sound, have a great sound chain, top quality reproducers be they buds, cans or the best room shakers a kings ransom can buy, there is still no shame is adjusting for room acoustics or hearing problems due to disease, too much time as a roadie, or just advancing age.Although may the Gods save us from $99 USB turntables and most motherboard-mounted audio solutions, it IS possible to make a decent copy of a recording in any format and clean it up without destroying the visceral experience of what made that recording great.  Again, almost every purist will have a slightly different take on how to get there, but all will agree there are two key points - don't waste your time on making a FLAC (lossless) copy of a 56k MP3, and DO make sure that you LIKE the sound that is traveling that last inch from your headphones to your eardrums.  I have found over the last several months that the RS 180's provide one great way to get there, without breaking the bank, your neck, or your lease. I listened to a half-dozen competitors before buying this model, and I even asked a friend to NOT buy me what HE liked the best for HIS needs ( Bluetooth connection between his iPod and his active-suppression Bose cans so he can listen to e-books and music while mowing the lawn).  Don't get me wrong - his choice was a valid one for him, but if you are looking to kick back a bit and focus on the music without too much racket in the background, the open-back RS 180's are a very convenient and enjoyable option for you to consider.  For me, they are definitely well worth the money.
