VExceptional sound, good comfort, great mobility , echo during tv
p315
sg5
VVolume - excellent, maximum setting is very uncomfortableBass - excellent.Clarity - excellent - meets Sennheiser reputation.Overall sound quality - surprising and extraordinary -- almost as good as my Sennheiser 580's (which are wired).User friendliness - setup is intuitive.Signal - excellent, was able to walk full extent of home with zero loss of signal.Bluetooth - nope.  The choice here was between your entertainment center/some fixed location vs your iphone/laptop, and the choice was clearly made for home entertainment situations.  Another choice was between the superior "Kleer" audio transmission and the inferior bluetooth signal, and considerations that favored audiophile needs won out.Interference - no conflict with wifi or other signals, as some are reporting.Comfort - excellent, but people with large ears may have a problem right away.  Otherwise these are soft and extremely lightweight.Aesthetics - large and goofy, though nowhere near as ridiculous as the Pioneer SE-DRS3000C.  These clearly favor function over form.Privacy - none.  If your intent is to prevent the world from knowing you listen to Justin Bieber or Katy Perry, then these headphones will not keep your shameful secret.Sound isolation - these aren't isolation headphones.Controls - if you've read more than five reviews then you already know the controls weren't designed to be used blindly.  It would be nice at times to be able to adjust the volume without taking them off, so I'll play around with putting on tape so my fingers can feel out the controls better.  Edit: Solution for the controls issue: glue a couple objects to the volume buttons after you are certain you approve of the other features of the headphones.  I used those little rubber thingies you can get in most hardware stores, and now I can feel the volume buttons (and the power button in between them) with no problem.With tv - this is the unit's single greatest point against it.  What people are reporting about the echo is true, so unless your tv has a special syncing option you won't be able to watch this with your headphones on while other people watch without them.  The only real alternative is to buy extra headphones (the unit can support up to four) and have the whole family wearing them, though people who don't need them will probably resent this pretty quickly.  This single design mishap is costing the headphones a full star, but in light of the headphones greatest strengths (sound quality and signal strength) I'll be keeping them anyway because the primary motive for buying them was for work, and not for the entertainment center.Solution for the problem many people are reporting regarding the signal cutting out at low volumes: Max out the volume on your primary source (in my case my laptop computer) and control the volume from the headphones.  This eliminates the cutout and, oddly enough, a high pitch whine (don't ask me why).
