VExcellent!
p333
sg5
VI was upgrading from the RS120's, which I purchased reconditioned through Amazon for about $80 as an experiment to see how well the whole wireless media experience would work for me; it worked well enough with those, but when I began noticing more interference (neighbors' wireless handset phone calls, static) I decided it was time to really jump in and spend more for higher quality. After looking at the various models available from Sennheiser, as well as others (like Sony), I was convinced the 180's were exactly what I wanted, given my price-point and quality requirements.I feel I made an excellent choice--absolutely NO buyer's remorse here. With the digital signal there is absolutely NO interference or lag or anything disruptive that I've encountered. The sound itself is beautifully crisp with what seems like a very full range to me. Full disclosure: I am by no means an "audiophile". But I know what sounds good and what doesn't, and have what I believe are reasonable expectations pertaining to the middle, higher and lower ends of the sound spectrum (high tweets to low bass), and so far I can't detect any faults with the Sennheiser 180's. Explosions sounds deep and rumbly like they should, voices are easily discerned, high-note violin strains are suitably clean and clear. Perhaps these earphones only sound so much better to me because of the constant static, etc, of the 120's, but I've had my share of wired headphones in my day and I honestly can't recall ever hearing better sound. And the comfort! These are SO comfortable on my ears. I was a little hesitant at first because these are "over-ear" as opposed to "on-ear" like the 120's were, but I need not have been concerned at all--the velour cups make it extremely easy to forget one is even wearing earphones, and because the backs are "open", enough air passes through that my inner ear is happy and I don't get that claustrophobic feeling that "closed" over-ear headphones always give me. Also, unlike the 120's, these STAY ON--no slipping and sliding out of place should I happen to move my head into anything other than an upright vertical position, so I'm able to wear these around the house while I do other things with no constant re-adjusting them on my head. What's interesting is that even though I wear glasses and the 180's appear to have better grip than the 120's, I get no discomfort from these whereas the 120's would start to press the arms of my glasses into the sides of my skull pretty noticeably after an hour or two. Also, the signal has no problem traveling through the floors and ceiling of my 3-level home.Honestly, these are fantastic, IMO. If I could change only one thing though, I'd have made the buttons on the right side easier to detect and identify. As others have pointed out, they're very smooth and almost flush, so it's a little too easy to click, say, the power button instead of the upper volume control. I plan to try the trick mentioned here with a tiny dab of glue to add a bump to the power button so I can instantly tell what's what.Pro Tip: if you buy these and instantly notice a lot of popping sounds with dialog and such, be sure to turn down the volume of the providing device (like my receiver) and that stuff will go away. With the 120's I had to have the volume cranked up to like 60 in order for the headphones to stop turning themselves off prematurely and to provide more signal strength (apparently), but with these, dialing down to 30 was just fine, better, in fact, and also happens to be the "comfortable" volume level of my surround sound system whenever I'm using it instead, so no more having to remember to dial down the volume if I unplug the earphones, lolThese even look better on the fireplace mantle beside my 60" plasma tv than the 120's did. Very sleek and modern-looking.UPDATE: the "dab of glue" trick for the volume buttons didn't work for me. For whatever reason, the Krazy glue I used wouldn't dry properly on the buttons' plastic and spread out to the sides too easily. Luckily I was able to clean them up without messing up the buttons.So instead now I've settled for small pieces of duct tape with enough extra tape jutting out that my finger can feel them over each button. Not as pretty, but practical.
