VI can't begin to describe how much I love these. I've owned many headphones over the years, but I'm on a Sennheiser streak in the most recent of them. I currently own HD590s, HD598s, and now these (with a second headset). The 590s and 598s both have a tiny bit more ear space, but these fit and are very comfortable nonetheless. Given the history, it should be apparent I'm a fan of open air headphones. Not being tethered by a wire but getting the kind of audio quality I've come to expect out of my other sets is just amazing. I've had them on my head for hours and hours since they arrived recently.Before I bought these, I was looking at the RS 160, 170, and 180 models. I read a lot of conflicting info and reached out to Sennheiser and talked with a tech there. He clarified to me that you can independently control the volume on each headset when having multiple paired without issue (confirmed) and that you can connect any of the 160/170/180 to the 180 base station (as well as the other base stations). As I really wanted open air, the 180s were the only option.I don't find the pairing system very complicated, and had no difficulty getting more than one connected. Range has been spectacular, and I can listen to music from anywhere indoors where I live. As I'm not in a single family house, I have to still pay attention to sound levels when it gets late at night, so the plan is to add two more headsets to the mix and have an alternative for group movie watching late at night. The open air backs let you still talk through the headphones...should make for awesome late night movie nights.An extra bit that I really like is that the headphones shipped with Eneloop AAAs and not some other, lesser option. As a result I was able to take them out of the box and wear them right away (Eneloops are designed to ship charged, hold that charge, and be used immediately before recharging is necessary).All in all, I couldn't be happier about this purchase and can't wait to use them more.
