VGreat value
p351
sg5
VI've heard very-high-end audio systems before (costing deep into five-figures), and I own a pair of Sennheiser HD 600 wired headphones, so I have experience with a good set of cans.  That said, I wouldn't quite call the RS 180 audiophile grade. However, for anything less than highly critical listening, these headphones deliver clean, quality sound that should satisfy just about anyone.I don't use these for listening to music, I use them with my TV when I want to watch a movie late at night.  They allow me to mute the TV's speakers while listening through the headphones at whatever volume level I like without worrying about waking others in the house.  I wasn't expecting much bass response, but they do have a respectable low end.  Nothing that would match a good home theater system, but as much or more than what my TV's built-in speakers offer down low.I debated whether to splurge and get the RS 220 or these.  Reviews I read both at Amazon and elsewhere made me decide the RS 180 was the way to go.  Many have reported having problems with static or broken signals with the RS 220, which, apparently, uses a different wi-fi system.  I've had no problems with the signal using my RS 180.  Sound quality is very clear and static free.  My listening distance from the headphones' base is usually around 15 feet, but I've walked into other rooms while wearing these and found the signal remains clear and strong.  The headphones are comfortable even after wearing them for several hours.  Battery life has never been an issue.  Sennheiser claims these can be used for up to 24 hours on a single charge (two AAA Eneloop rechargeable batteries are included).  I've never even come close to testing that claim as I stop watching TV long before these things run out of juice.  The RS 220, in contrast, only lasts up to 8 hours on a single charge, which could be an issue if multiple people were to use it during the day.  The RS 220 reportedly does have slightly better sound quality, but you pay through the nose to get that little extra bit of quality.  There's a point of diminishing returns with everything, and for my purposes, the RS 180 is the right balance of price and performance.The only real niggle I have is with the volume buttons on the headphones.  The volume-up button is actually bigger than the volume-down button.  It's easy enough to find and press while wearing the headset.  The button right next to it is the power button.  It has a raised surface that aids in locating it by feel.  The next button over is the volume-down button.  It's notably smaller than the volume-up button (form over function) and can be a little hard to find when you're feeling for it while wearing the headphones.  Sometimes I have to remove the headset to find it, although I'm getting better at finding it the more I wear these.  It's not a huge deal since I don't have to adjust the volume often, but it's an area for improvement if Sennheiser ever decides to redesign these.As others have mentioned, there is a very slight time delay in the wireless signal (emphasis on "very slight"), so if your TV's speakers are turned up while you're listening to the headphones, you can hear the slightest echo effect.  If your TV's speakers are turned down enough relative to the headphones, you might not even notice it.  The signal delay really is quite small, so the effect is minor, but, apparently, not all wireless headphone suffer from this, so it needs to be mentioned at least.Despite these minor issues, I still give 5 stars to the RS180 for its solid performance at this price point.[Edit: 12-1-13] Just wanted to update this review with a word about Sennheiser's excellent customer support.  One of my kids knocked my headphones and its base off their shelf, which damaged them internally so that they would no longer produce sound.  I sent them in to Sennheiser with a note about how they got broken.  I acknowledged the existing warranty might not cover such abuse and stated I was willing to pay for the repair if needed.  A couple weeks later, Sennheiser mailed me what looks to be a new (but is perhaps refurbished) unit and base with all of the needed wires (I had only mailed in the headphones and base unit without the wires).  No questions asked, and no cost to me.  First class customer service.
