VAlmost perfect high-end headphones
p357
sg5
VAfter spending a few days researching the various wireless headset options, I settled on the Sennheiser RS 180 wireless headphones. There was some heavy internal deliberation between the this set (RS 180) and it's cousin the RS 170. Both are overall quite similar, with the most significant difference being the 170 is a closed design, whereas the 180 is open.Others have covered the differences between closed vs open, so I won't reiterate. The other consideration was the comparably priced Sony MDR-DS6500.UNBOXING:I received the order quickly and everything was in good shape. The unboxing experience was decent, and a was pleasantly surprised to find little touches like a vanity sleeve to hide cables. Not necessary, but a thoughtful detail.SETUP:Setup was quick and the rechargeable batteries came pre-charged, meaning I was listening to music in about 10 minutes from unboxing, after a short review of the setup guide.EXPERIENCE:I've owned a number of Senn's over the years (HD 280, HD500's) and they've always delivered accurate sound with a luxurious cushioned feel. However, with the RS 180 being  wireless, I was somewhat apprehensive of the sound quality, being my first foray into cord-cutting. Needless to say I am impressed.Being in my 30's, my hearing is no probably no match for a 20 year olds. That said, for TV and casual console gaming the sound quality is really excellent, even considering the nature of the source inputs. I did briefly consider the true audiophile positioned solution, the RS 220, but at $600 and a spotty wireless range, it was quickly out of the question.The headphones themselves are super comfy to wear for long periods and the open design means you won't get too hot. Wireless range is decent. I was able to walk around everywhere in my 2 Bedroom apartment without any signal loss or interruption.Others have mentioned some lag, however I plugged the receiver directly into the TV (Sharp Aquos) and when playing a game on the Wii with the volume turned up on both the TV and the headphones I was unable to detect any discernible delay. That is not to say there is none at all, but if there is, it's would almost surely below 200ms.IMPROVEMENTS:+ Buttons: I recall reading somewhere that Sennheiser's motivation behind the flat/flush button design of the headphone mounted controls, was to prevent accidental button pushing, when lying on one's side. While it looks like the company has been succesful in that regard, sadly it appears they've compromised on the overall user experience when it comes to changing volume. Hopefully the next iteration we'll see both goals being achieved. One random suggestion could be to have the buttons *indented* instead of protruding outwards? Either way, however it is solved, there needs to be some form of tactile feedback on the two most important buttons (Vol up/Vol down). Additionally it would be a good idea to spatially separate the volume controls from the other buttons.+ Sensor: How neat would it be if the trend towards smarter electronics (ie smartphones) in consumer electronics were adopted? For example, include a simple pressure sensor to let the headset's micro controller know when to turn the itself on an off. Of course, there would need probably need to be a suitable delay built in, so that after 2min or 5 minutes of it not being worn it shuts down, then as soon as you put it on your head it reconnects automatically. No fuss or user intervention needed and battery power is still conserved. As it stands power off is determined by whether a signal is playing or not, but that again places additional behavior (turn off the tv/sound source etc), on the user.+Digital input: One thing that the Sony MDR-DS6500 has going for it is digital input. Unfortunately Sennheiser only includes this on their most expensive model, the RS 220. At around $250 bucks for this set, I think this should be a standard feature on this model too.So there you have it. The RS 180's are a fine (if somewhat pricey) pair of headphones that will almost certainly make you smile.
