VTypical terrible Sennheiser ergonomics
p542
sg5
VThese are really great sounding and comfortable for me. I've got a big head and it just fits me on the biggest size setting, but it does, and is comfortable. This is not a surprise - I've had other Sennheiser headphones with the velour ear pads and they are super comfortable and they know how to make a good sounding headphone.Having said that, Sennheiser's ability to make ergonomically sound products is dreadful. I've never seen one with sensible button layout or generally well thought out products, aside from the the drivers and microphones.- As everyone points out, the buttons are difficult to tell apart by feel and are all next to each other on the headphone, where they can't be seen when you are wearing them out. It's just a joke that the entire bottom surface of the right headphone is slick and with non-distinct features to highlight the different buttons. The mute / off button is in the middle of the volume buttons. WTF! The balance buttons are right next to the volume and there is no way to see if you have the balance centered, only listening. I can't understand how they make garbage like this. It's only the ergonomics that they are so terrible at. It's like they have someone high up in the company who makes the final decision on ergonomics and is clueless.- I expected the button problems because everyone has been so vocal about them. What really baffles me is that the headphones and base BOTH need to be turned on when you want to listen to them. If I have the headphones on the charging base and take them off, I can't understand why the base can't turn on automatically when I take the headphones off of the base. The headphones should turn on, too.- The main LED (multi-function LED) blinks all the time. I have the headphone base near my TV and it blinks whenever I am using the headphones. It's in my line of sight, so if it is working, it is distracting. It might be telling me that there is one headphone linked or two. It might be telling me that things are normal. It might be telling me the status of the charge. Lots of blink codes, but it never just is on steady. It's not like LEDs are expensive -- there could have been several if they thought it was so important to show all of that stuff.These headphones are too comfortable and sound too good to return, but they are firmly in the camp of products I just don't like, but can't find one that is better. I really wish Sennheiser would get their act together. They have the sound quality down. If they would only raise to the level of mediocre ergonomics, they would truly be great.Update after using these 2-3 hours every day for a month:They still sounds good.The ergonomics are showing even more details of how bad it is.:- You need to turn on the base all the time. The base isn't hard enough to push the button without the base sliding all over, so pushing the on button is a two handed affair.- I use these every day and still struggle to tell what button are which. It isn't impossible, but it's surprisingly hard. I have to focus to hit the right button. I can say that this is the only product I own where I need to focus to operate it.- Adding the balance button nonsense; if I lean my head back on the couch and turn my head to the right, the couch pillow hits one of the buttons, changing the balance or volume.
