VVery good sound quality.  I have been using this now for about 2 weeks.  I had been using the Sennheiser RS 130 for about 15 yrs and was consistently pleased.  I finally purchased this new product, RS 180 as my 130 was beginning to cut out even when I was right in front of the transmitter (I think it was the batteries and simply long term wear).  The RS 130 did last a long time with no visible signs of deterioration so I am hoping for the same with the RS 180.  My only complaints is that I preferred (so far at least) the RS 130 on/off switch on the head phones (simple, easy to use on one side of the head phones) and volume control (very simply, gradiant dial on the other side).  The RS 180 requires to first turn on the transmitter, and THEN turn on the head phones.  I suspect that I will quickly get used to this change, but have not yet.  The other thing I initially don't like as much is the volume and on/off buttons on the RS 180.  They are all push buttons (push in and release) for their incremental activation (push repeatedly for the volume to go up  or down).  The power button is in btw the volume buttons and can easily be confused.  It would have been much more intelligent to have the power button on the other ear/side so as to not confuse.Finally, I have not found the  RS 180s to be as comfortable.  I was surprised by this as the reviews I read commented about how comfortable these are.  I may just need to get used to them but I do not find them to be as comfortable as the RS 130s were.The reason I rated them a 4/5 with these short comings is the sound quality.  The sound is very good for wireless.  Hopefully I will get accustomed to the other things I do not like as much with time, but 'getting used to' things is not normally something I expect for a device that costs $200 from a quality brand such as Sennheiser.
