VBrad
p550
sg9
VVerified Purchase
p551
sg11
VDecember 13, 2014
p552
sa(dp553
g2
F4.0
sg3
VA FIVE STAR -- almost
p554
sg5
VI used Sennheiser 120s for years to help me hear dialogue on TV and movies with good results.  I bought the RS 180 after reading reviews here and elsewhere, thinking I can do even better with improved phones. Overall, I am not disappointed.SET UP:  No printed manual.  The quick setup guide is very sparse indeed - just diagrams, no words.  Although these are headphones (how complicated can that be?) there are different colored lights that blink, multi-function buttons, etc.  A more detailed "quick" setup guide would have been useful. I recommend watching the 4-minute installation video on the Sennheiser site before installing.  The full detailed manual is on the included CD and on line. I recommend downloading it to your computer or iPad for a searchable manual.  Instructions say to allow 16 hours for the first battery charge, but my charge light went out after 2 hours and worked fine.THE GOOD:* RANGE: I hoped the 180 would have at least as good range as the 120, allowing me to wander about the house and garden without interference or drop out. The range on the 180 is at least as good or better than the 120.*  SOUND QUALITY: Excellent, noticeably better than the 120.  Deep(er) base, bright treble. The automatic level control (ALC), which is toggled on/off, boosts quiet sections and quiets down noisier ones (i.e., commercials). I wouldn't use this feature for music, but for TV and movies, the dialogue stands out.* MUTE BUTTON: A small but useful feature: The "multi-function" button on the headset also operates as a mute.  This is handy for those annoying commercials.  On my previous phones if you wanted mute you had to turn down the volume.* COMFORT:  Snug fit, these don't fall off my head when I bend or move, but I can wear them for hours without discomfort.  They are considerably lighter than my old pair, I forget I have them on.* FLEXIBLE USE:  There is a cable included for use with the earphone jack as well as an RCA cable for audio outputs.  This is important, as you have the option of whether to silence the internal speakers of your sound source or have them independently controlled (are you watching/listening alone or with someone else who needs the speakers on?)THE NOT SO GOOD:* CONVENIENCE:  Unit must be manually turned on in two places before use - both transmitter and headset.  My previous set had just one on/off switch on the headset.  This is a minor inconvenience.  Unit shuts off automatically in a few minutes if unattended to save batteries, but it must be manually started.* CONTROLS: As was stated numerous times in these reviews, the headset controls are difficult to locate in use.  I agree.  In my opinion this is the only real downside to the 180 - I prefer old-fashioned analogue dials that you can feel.  Why Sennheiser didn't test usage, read the reviews, and simply put raised guides on the controls makes me shake my head-isn't volume control a rather basic function to headphones? One reviewer here said he used epoxy to make his own raised guide - I may do that if I don't get the hang of it soon.  I'll follow up after a few weeks of use.ONE MORE THING: Several reviews here mentioned a noticeable delay when the headphones are used with the speakers of the sound source causing an annoying "echo" effect.  Unlike my previous set, this was the case with the 180 when I first tried them with my wife listening through the TV speakers.  This would have been a deal-killer had I not been able to correct it.  However, on my late model LG TV under audio settings there are controls called "AV Sync" where I can adjust the audio stream of either the headset or the sound source.  The problem was quickly solved.  If your TV doesn't have this audio setting, it may be possible to work around it another way, such as using the TV or receiver's RCA audio output instead of the headphone jack.SUMMARY:Excellent sound, especially for a wireless set, reasonably priced for the quality, comfortable to wear, reasonably easy to set up and use.  I would give it a 5 star rating if....well, you know, those controls.ADDITIONAL COMMENT REGARDING THOSE CRAPPY CONTROLS: After a few weeks trying to get the hang of using the controls while wearing the headphones, I gave up -- it's just too difficult. I took the advice of one reviewer and placed a drop of epoxy on the control knob (off/on, etc).  It works perfectly, and now using the controls while wearing the phones is easy.  Before you apply the epoxy, be sure to seal the cracks surrounding the button with tape so glue doesn't drip inside and freeze the button.  I doubt the warranty would apply in that case. My 4-star rating stands rather than a perfect 5 -- there is no excuse for the poor design when the solution would be so simple.
