VI've enjoyed Sennheiser wireless headphones for many years. The old pair was showing its age so I updated to the RS 180. These are far more comfortable to wear than the previous pair. The sound is slightly better. I can now make volume balance adjustments separately for each ear.Now for the controls. Not sure why the ease of operation wasn't a goal for this model. With the previous model I could click the on and off button on the left earphone. I could adjust the volume by turning a wheel on the right earphone. (no left/right balance adjustment). Now I have to first turn on the device by clicking on a button on the base. This is actually a two-handed operation as the base needs to be held in place when pushing the button lest it be shoved off its perch. (At least this button goes off automatically when the headphones are charging).Next I have to turn on the headphones by looking directly at the headphones. Although there are raised "pimples" on the on/off button they are very difficult to locate by touch. I have to look. It is difficult to feel the other buttons, all smooth, one each for vol. up, vol. down, L and R balance, since they are all crammed together in a 1 3/4" line and the buttons become smaller and smaller until the last balance button is smaller than the tip of my little finger. So one must look in order to find the buttons. (After a month I have learned by feel to turn the volume up...but not down). Obviously this requires taking the headphones off first and the adjustments can only be tested by placing the headphones back on and then taking them off again if further adjustments are needed. What a shame for a design where form trumps function.This device would easily deserve 5 stars if it weren't for the lousy controls.
