VHow I solved the echo problem with the Sennheiser RS 180 and now have a new problem!
p577
sg5
VI have two sets of these headphones.  The first set I bought a about three years ago and I use them with a TV at my main home.  They are wonderful for me.  I have a problem common to many men, hearing loss that interferes with my wife's enjoyment of TV watching with me as I have to turn the sound up too high for her comfort.  These headphones solved that problem.  They have excellent, clear sound  and I can control my own volume.  We have a second home so I bought another set for it.  There I have a modern, 52 inch Sony mounted on the wall.  Like so many big TV's it has analog out and digital optical out.  I used the analog out to connect my Polk Audio soundbar...it doesn't have digital optical inputs and I enjoy good sound from it. I then connected the Sennheiser's to the optical out with a digital to analog convertor.  I GOT AN ECHO!  It was so bad I could only use them when the soundbar was off.  No more watching TV with my wife with the proper sound for both of us!  Too loud for her, too soft for me.  She started using earplugs.  I was bummed.  I poked around on the internet and found that the delay and consequent echo was not unusual and no one had a solution that worked for me.  The headphones, a little pricey, simply sat there holding down paper.  I would revisit the issue from time to time, never finding a solution.I don't know why the last hunt for a solution finally worked, but it did!  I bought , from Cable Electronics Labs, their A/V Distribution amplifier model AV400.  I ran a cable from analog out to the amp and connected the soundbar and headphones to the amp and the echo disappeared!  Marital bliss ensued.March 10, 2014A new problem has surfaced!  I started getting sound only through the right earpiece.  I found that by pulling the 3.5 mm audio cord out a mm or two from the transmitter both sides would work.  A bad connector, I thought.  I tried three others, all the same.  Something must be wrong with the connection inside the transmitter.  Long out of warranty, I'm afraid. I've removed two stars.December 20, 2014Problems all solved!  The fault was mine.  I hooked these up incorrectly.  I'm not a ninny and usually have no problems with simple connections but I have a wall mounted TV and couldn't see behind it and inserted the audio cables by feel.  I finally realized that one cord was in an audio input rather than the output.  Once corrected the headphones work very well and, once again, the echo is solved with the audio distribution amp.  I have changed the rating to five stars and encourage anyone with an echo problem from their TV to try my solution.
