VI ordered a refurbished RS180 to replace my existing top of the line Philips. The Philips was not bad, but definitely not execellent also. Bass was "hollow" and treble is flat, and its reception was problematic, frequently jumps channel even if I was working inside the living room, where the transmitter was placed.I've tried the RS180 in shop and wanted it for quite sometime but is keeping away from it deal to its price. But the longer I wear the Philips, my desire grew even more stronger, so I ordered a refurbished one from Amazon marketplace at around 50% of the original price.This is the first time I have ordered a refurbished item and I originally expected it would come in some kind of "white box". However, when I first received the package, I was shocked - it was wrapped in transparent polymer only. I said to myself that this must be crazy, who would send a headphone with a polymer wrapping! I opened it, and as I've speculated, it was seriously damaged. The plastic part left hand band had been totally broken and was holding in place by the wires only. Quite disappointed and I filed a claim and return it.Here's the best part I like about Amazon, most sellers were quite ethical and my replacement headphone came in again within 2 weeks. These time I pay special caution to ask the seller to send it with the proper packing - a box.I am very happy with RS180, it was as good as new. Sound quality is the best I have experienced so far. It is open-air designed so your wife will hear a little bit of what you are hearing, but this let it wear more comfortbaly, even for a long time. Reception is good, thpugh not excellent. I am living in a 90 sq.m apartment and there are dead corners, even if I keep all the doors open. But it covers around 90% of my apartment so I am quite satified. It open jump channels (or recover from a weak signal) occasionally which is much better than the Philips.It comes with the SANYO AAA rechargebale and if I am careless enough to forget recharging it, I can get spares to replace it. An interesting point of my Philips is that it is incompatible with the SANYO. I don't know why but if you put the SANYO into the Philips, it will continuously ask you to recharge it.I am very happy with my RS180. The lesson learned though, is you will better always ask the sellers to ship it with a box, even if that will cost you a few more bucks.
