VFreedom of movement
p601
sg5
VBefore purchasing the RS 180 Digital Wireless Headphone System I did a lot of research. When I listen to music during breaks at work I need to use headphones and I also need to be able to move around. Wired headphones were too confining, and I underestimated how much I would appreciate the ability to listen to music and simultaneously get up from the desk, walk down the hall to the copy machine, and move freely about the office.I wanted headphones with a wireless link that was completely transparent, as good as a wired link, because I'm pretty fussy about audio after working in the recording and broadcast industries for many years. The Kleer chipset with an OFDM modulated 2.4 GHz digital RF link that is used in the RS 180 has met my expectations. The transmitter is smart enough to frequency hop to a channel that is free from interference from wireless routers and other signals on the 2.4 GHz band.These headphones can be worn comfortably for hours due to the open-air design. The audio quality is good, although I can detect a little too much harmonic distortion on low-frequency sounds. The midrange and high end are crystal-clear and undistorted. There is absolutely no background hiss detectable, even in the quietest (ambient noise) location that I could find. The OFDM modulation scheme completely eliminates momentary disturbances due to multipath and fading. There is absolutely no detectable change in the audio as you turn your head or move around, something that no analog FM system can match. When the signal is insufficient for error-free audio, the headphones fade to silence rapidly. Upon restoration of signal they fade back up smoothly. The transmission range is adequate for their intended purposes.In short, these are the best wireless headphones that I've ever heard. My only complaint has been voiced by other reviewers. Sennheiser made a bad design decision when they decided to turn off the base station transmitter after a 5 minute loss of link to the headphones. As a result you need to return to the transmitter and push the power-on button again when this happens. The timeout needs to be longer; perhaps 15 minutes.
