VThis unit replaced my wired Sennheiser HD-580 phones (I finally got tired of replacing the wires every year or two).While the sound isn't quite as good as the 580's, it's awfully close. Far better sound than I'd expected to find in a wireless set.Range is impressive. I've only gone 50 feet or so from the base unit, but the distance included two sets of 2x6 walls plus 1 2x4 wall. I heard a very brief dropout once or twice, and they may have simply been the transmitter adjusting to the new receiver position. Other than those short quiet spells, the sound and reception have been excellent, with only minimal loss in volume.So far I'd give these phones 5 stars.The only reason I knocked a star off is because, as many have said, the small controls are a pain to find; definitely not something you just reach for by feel. I'll probably put small pieces of tape on one or two of the buttons to make it easy to know where my fingers are.I was worried about the 'ghosting' that some people have commented on. It's just not there if you follow Sennheiser's very clear instructions and turn your speakers off. If you leave them on, then it's perfectly normal for open-ear phones to let the ambient sound through and give that "echo".The other thing I worried about was synchronization with the video source. If there's an audio delay with the RS-180, I sure can't see it. I've watched about 25 hours of video so far and the lips and sound look perfectly fine to me.One other thing: as another reviewer or two noted, these phones do NOT have dynamic surround sound; that's a feature of the RS-170. Frankly, I don't think the RS-180 needs it.Overall, I'd highly recommend these phones, especially at Amazon's current price.Sennheiser RS 180 Digital Wireless Headphone System with Dynamic Surround Sound
