VGreat sound, great range
p613
sg5
VJust unboxed this and tested it out.  I gotta say I don't understand some of these reviews from people saying how much they suck and how cheap they are and how poor the range is.  The sound is pretty much the best headphone sound I've heard, short of the sound you can get out of $400-500 MM550s or Dr. Dre Beats or other noise cancelling+SRS headphones.  But the range is fantastic for my needs.  I can go everywhere in my 3000 sq/ft house with no droppage or static.  I can go to the end of my 50 ft. driveway and then it starts breaking up.  So, can I get 300M or whatever they claim here? No, but that's line of site I'm sure.  I can get everywhere in my 3 story home and all the way around the outside of the house and the garage.I also was able to pair up a second pair of RS 180s very easily.  I don't get the guy who claimed the manual stunk.  It said how to do it...I did it...it worked.  Essentially, hold the ON button down on all the headsets for 7+ seconds, then hold the ON button on the base down for 7 seconds...then within 30 seconds, the blinking levels off and they're paired.  I don't understand what was so difficult.  Perhaps the instructions I got on the CD/DVD it came with were more updated?There was also a review somewhere about how cheap they felt and about the sound leakage.  I guess that's a matter of personal preference because I found them just fine for me.  I'm thinking it was a design decision such that if they'd made them solid-feeling aluminum or something, they'd be uncomfortably heavy.  As it stands, they're super light and the light, puffy velvety ear cups are very smooth and comfy.  They do leak a tiny bit of the sound, but it's not quite as bad as someone let on.  It's not like you can hear what someone is listening to from across the room, but if you know the song, sure, you can make it out if they've got it up high enough.  I had to get about 12" from my wife's ear before I could hear what she was listening to.  I wouldn't really call that bad sound leakage and a reason to not get these.  In fact, it's that quality which also lets you hear someone talking to you while you've got them on.  Some over-the-ear phones are so sound-tight that you can't hear a police car if it were in front of you.  These are such that you can easily hear people in the room at the same time without having to pull them off and go "WHAT!!??"Anyway, fantastic sound, great base, great highs, comfortable, good range, and more.  I found them worth the money.  I have 2 headsets with my base so my wife and I can watch a movie or TV show with the kids in the next room without bothering them or having them hear adult subject matter they're not ready for.UPDATE:  Minor con...when you have multiple people listening to the same audio stream on multiple RS 180's, when you turn your volume up, everyone gets their volume turned up.  When they turn theirs down, your's gets turned down.  This is fine as long as you're all the same deafness.  If someone is hard of hearing though, either you're going to get blasted or they won't hear it.
