VCouldn't be happier with 'em
p630
sg5
VI bought this wireless headphone system to use while watching TV late at night, so I won't wake my spouse who sleeps upstairs above the TV room.  I am very pleased in all respects.  The sound quality is excellent -- on par with expensive, cable-connected phones.  The digital system prevents the hiss often present in analog wireless.  I don't ask much, in the terms of "range";  I'm sitting but 10-15 ft from the base-station.  I can walk into other rooms on the same floor without drop-off, though if I go upstairs from the base station, I do encounter some occasional zones where reception drops off.  I can't say as how good the reception would be if I went outside to deck or yard -- an occurrence unlikely at the moment, since it's sub-zero outside where I live.  I haven't encountered any interference to the headphone system caused by other appliances (wireless telephones and WiFi) in my house.  Nor have I encountered any interference to the other appliances caused by the headphone system.  Your mileage may differ.The base-station cradle unit is relatively compact and hides behind my wide-screen LCD display, out of sight.  You have to be careful placing the headphones on the cradle, to insure the contacts engage for charging.  However, there's an amber LED that lights while the headphone set is charging, so it's obvious when contact has been made.The headphones are rather large and ugly, but not heavy or uncomfortable.  I can wear them for hours with no particular discomfort -- though in warmer weather, I might have a different opinion.  (It's winter, now, where I reside, so I don't yet know if I'll find them "sweaty" around the ears when worn in the heat/humidity of summer.)  The control buttons on the headphones take some getting used-to:  there are small buttons for (in this order, L to R):  volume up;  power on/off;  volume down; adjust volume balance towards the left channel;  and adjust volume balance towards the right channel.  The buttons are very small, close together;  and insufficiently raised above the background.  With practice, however, I've learned to use all of them without having to remove the headset.  They just take some getting used to.All things considered, I highly recommend them.  They're not inexpensive, but they work (for me) really well.
