VI've had these about a week and I think they're great.  My previous set of headphones was a wired set of Grado SR-60s, and these sound every bit as good to me - but wireless!  Indoor range seems to be about 60 feet through 5 or 6 walls.  I can essentially use them anywhere in my house and some outside as well.  Near the perimeter of the range you will get some cutting out, but step one foot closer and they're as clear as they are one foot from the base.  There is no static.I wear them for several hours a day and they're quite comfortable.  They have a soft velour pad that goes around your ear and more at the top of your head.  People who are bald or balding will probably find them pretty comfortable compared to unpadded bands.  They twist and adjust quite a bit to fit different size and shaped heads.The base is modern and nice looking.  I wish it were a little heavier because it's hard to turn the base on and off with one hand without pushing it over.  The headphones fit easily over the top for storage and charging.The batteries last about the rated 24 hours before requiring a recharge.  You do get about a half hour of warning that the batteries are getting close to being discharged.  They are just Ni-Cad AAA batteries so you should just be able to replace them with standard, inexpensive rechargeable AAAs when they eventually die.Build quality is excellent.  They feel like expensive headphones and look nice as well.  But they are expensive!  Cost is about four times what my Grados cost, and even a few times more than some of the less expensive Sennheiser models.  I was willing to pay the extra amount for an open headphone with superior sound quality and some extra range, but others might be just as happy with the cheaper SR 170 or SR 160 models given their circumstances.
