VI just received the RS 180\u2019s to listen to music, internet radio, or any computer audio as I moved around the house. My former solution was to use strategically placed portable speakers attached to Apple AirPort Expresses sending the music via iTunes or other audio via Rogue Amoeba\u2019s Airfoil Software.That has worked getting the sound to various locations, but of course the sound quality was marginal, and the stereo effect was missing.The Sennheiser RS 180\u2019s have given me the ability to listen to high quality sound in full stereo, with unfettered movement.When setting up the 180\u2019s the first \u201cproblem\u201d I faced was that plugging the 180 transmitter into the headphone jack in the Mac killed the sound from the internal Mac speakers. It also meant the transmitter had to be located close to the Mac at one end of my house, preventing reliable reception at the other end of the house.That \u201cproblem\u201d was overcome by plugging the RS 180 transmitter into an AirPort Express centrally located in the house. Now with iTunes I can send the sound to both the computer and the AirPort Express at the same time. Additionally if I want to send any other audio from the Mac to the RS 180 headphones I can use Rogue Amoeba\u2019s AirFoil software. This gives me the ability to move anywhere in the house, or even limited distances outside the house, and listen to high quality sound.The Seenheiser RS 180\u2019s are a great product offering great portable sound. Highly recommended.
