sg3
VA pure delight
p1080
sg5
VI bought these headphones after all the positive comments I read about them, but either way, one is never sure, as sound is a personal thing, so I wasn't too sure if they were as good as all the reviews I read.Well let me put your mind to rest, that these are just plain, and simply amazing.Setup only takes a few minutes if that, and when I first put them on, I knew that I had made the right choice in headphones.The sound is crystal clear, and there is absolutely no noise, or hiss, or dropouts whatsoever.A few reviews I have read, said they had hiss in the background, and if that is the case, that was entirely due to the input signal not being set high enough.There is a switch on the Transmitter, for 0db and -8db.. If you are using a high level signal source such as a home audio stereo, set the switch to -8db and set the volume of your stereo to roughly about 3/4 of its volume range.If you are using a Laptop, Ipad or something like that, set the switch for 0db, as this allows a smaller signal , to be amplified properly.I have tried using these watching movies, as well as listening to music audio, and both sound equally amazing.The bass is not overpowering, but its tight and definitely present.Comfort of the headphones will probably be a personal thing also, as not all heads are created equal, but on my I suppose my regular size head, the comfort is very good,. I wear these headphones around the house all the time now listening to music while I am doing my chores, and I sometimes forget they are on my head.Of course you will never get the rated distance for the sound to travel, but for me, I can walk all upstairs in the house, and get as far as the outside of the back door before the sound drops off.What I like is the fact, there is no loss of audio quality until you do go out of range, and at that point, the sound just stops, and will come back on once you are in range again. There is no in between loss of audio quality up to that point.My only annoyance, which is a common one, is the placement of the switches on the headphones for volume and power and balance..They can be really hard to find when they are on your head, and you try to adjust the volume, but I think over time, it will become easier. That to me is a very small annoyance compared to the overall positive.I find now watching movies, with the ALC (automatic level control) turned on , I hear things, that I have never heard before.. Every little nuance and subtle passage is recognized, which makes for a very enjoyable movie experience.Keep in mind these are open headphones, as compared to closed headphones ( RS170 ) .Open headphones are not as tight around the ears, and will let some sound out, but at the same time, it gives you a more open , airy feel to the audio passages, which is what I like and also makes for a more comfortable fit . Anyone sitting beside you will probably be able to hear what you are listening to , so if that is an issue for you, then the RS170 headphones would be more your liking , as they are a closed set of headphones, being tighter sealed to your ears, keeping the sound more to yourself.But the RS170's don't have the ALC option, which is what I like very much with the RS180's.So if you are on the fence about these, make the plunge, as you wont have any regrets !
