VA great pair of headphones with a minor drawback.
p1086
sg5
V*As a disclaimer, I am reviewing within the first week of ownership. I have no judgement on this product's survivability.That being said, I find these headphones to be very high quality and professionally laid-out, but lacking in headband durability. The sound quality of these headphones is incredible. That aspect alone is worth $200. The open-back design leaks every sound to those around you, but the reason for this is to hit the consumer's ears with every possible tone in a clear manner. These headphones do that very well. Crisp, high tones do not damage your ears with their intensity. Bass is subtle, yet strong. They are simply elegant in sound design.The Stand and headphones themselves are very elegant as well. The button layout leaves something to be desired, but panning the audio left and right should really only happen during initial setup, and the volume controls are felt easily enough. Other than that, the stand and headphones feel very durable. Handle them with care, though. The headband seems very brittle, but the innards of the band seem to move independently of the band, so my fear of breaking these is minimal.The range really should not be a problem for anyone wanting to use these as a home entertainment system, or just an audiophile looking to find a nice pair of wireless headphones. I live in a cookie-cutter neighborhood, and these had no problem sending the signal through the walls of my house. I cannot say this will be true for everyone, in every type of house, obviously.These are hands-down the best pair of wireless headphones on the market. Do some research yourself. Try to figure out what is important to you in a headphone, and then come back and take a look at the 180's. The $200 price tag is well worth it for what you get out of the product.
