sg3
VQuality matches price
p1092
sg5
VIn this case, "you get what you pay for," seems to be an apt description of these Sennheiser wireless headphones.  In my opinion, the price tag is no small sum.  These headphones match in quality the price of the headphones.  I would add that the quality of the headphones match the price, no more or no less.  My prior experience with Sennheiser headphones has lead me to almost expect far more quality than even the price paid for said headphones.  Over two years ago, I owned the RS120 headphones from Sennheiser.  For the price I paid for those headphones, I believed that the quality far outpaced the price.  I know that hiss was an issue for many with the 120s, but I had a hard time detecting the dreaded hiss.  I found those headphones to be clear and extremely crisp.  Unfortunately, those headphones have never been found since I moved about two years ago.  After months of no success finding my much regarded Sennheiser RS120s, I decided to go ahead and purchase new headphones.  Sennheiser was the obvious choice for me since I was so impressed with my last set of Sennheisers.  The RS180s appealed to me as the obvious next step.  While the price was higher, I was definitely interested in the improved wireless technology.  For comparisons sake, it should be noted that my setup and environment are entirely different than the environment in which the 120s performed.  The 180s are connected to an Onkyo 808 receiver compared to the Onkyo 805 for the 120s.  Plus, I live in town with plenty of interference in the environment to be considered compared to a remote country setting for the 120s where there was little to no interference.  With those conditions set for reference, I must admit that I was not as impressed with the sound for the money with the 180s compared to the 120s.  Not that the 180s are of less quality or poor performance, I was just hoping for something to blow me away since the price was double.  Unless the setup and environment accounts for the difference, it is my impression that I got more bang for the buck with the 120s.  With the 180s, it seems that I obtained the quality for which I paid.  Again, no more or no less.It does seem to me that these RS180s have a more full ranged sound quality.  While the sound can be sharp and crisp with the appropriate content, the 180s seem to have a more well rounded and full bodied sound with both lows and highs.  It should be noted that I almost exclusively use the headphones for late at night HDTV and Blu-ray movie viewing.  As is so obviously mentioned with these types of headphones, they are excellent for superior sound quality when one does not want to wake up the wife and kids late at night while watching movies or catching up on shows on the DVR.  As for the wireless technology, I do not detect any interference or hiss with these RS180s.  Granted, I really could not detect much if any hiss in the 120s.  If I did at all, I thought I might have heard a little come through on the 120s with some high range content that tended to sound a little like that old high treble sound.  With these RS180s, that is not an issue at all.Regarding sound quality, I have no complaints at all.  I do find the RS180s to be an aesthetically pleasing set of home audio technology.  I have no problem setting this product on top of my audio stand in my living room.  Also, these headphones have plenty of range from the base.  I'm able to move around the house without any interference or degradation in audio quality.  If I were to have to mention any complaints with the headphones and base station, it would be along the lines of ease of use with the couple of buttons on the front of the base.  While the buttons are easily accessible and function properly, I find that after six months I still have to check the manual regarding the settings, pairing, and the meaning of the number of blinking lights in the time continuum.  As I mentioned, everything works fine.  I just don't find the set as user-friendly as I would like.  On the other hand, the buttons on the headphones work fine regarding to proper touch and pressure.  I also like the volume control buttons on the headphones themselves.  They are simple and easy to operate without any problems.All in all, I think the Sennheiser RS 180 headphone set is of an extreme high quality.  I would recommend these wireless headphones to my friends and family.  I would add that with the RS 180, that quality does not come cheaply for the typical homeowner with an average AV system.  While the quality of these headphones seem to match the price, I would add that the quality does not sound like it exceeds the price either.  In closing, I continue to be impressed with Sennheiser.
