VQuality item, but could be easier to use
p1104
sg5
VWe replaced a cheaper item with the Sennheiser RS 180 Digital Wireless Headphone System.  The cheaper one was half the price, but it was junk.  Don't buy a unit that uses infrared, which is directional, for the signal.  The Sennheiser is well built, sound quality is impressive, and it's appearance is elegant.  The only things I would change are the buttons on the earphones for power, volume and balance, maybe the way the unit is charged, and the way it turns on and off.The controls (volume up, volume down, and balance) are small and right next to one another, and I can't imagine trying to use them with the phones on.  It's very easy to hit the wrong button.  Maybe a knob on each ear pad would be better.  You could memorize which way to turn the knob.You can turn the unit off by holding down (not just pressing, because the buttons are made to do double duty) a button for a second on either the charger stand or the earphones, but it takes two pushes to turn it on (one for the charging stand, which contains the wireless transmitter, and one for the phones).  With a bit more smarts, the headphones could be made to standby in a low power mode, then ramp up when it detected a signal from the transmitter.  Maybe that's too much to ask for the price.For our installation, at least, it was an annoyance to have the charger integrated with the transmitter.  The transmitter has to be physically tied to the TV sound source with a cable, which limits your choices for where to plug in the charging station.  On the other hand, if the earphone charging station and transmitter were separated, I guess they might both need AC power, which would increase the cost of the unit.There is also a split-second delay between the time you hear something on the TV speakers, and the time you hear the same thing on the headphones.  Many people would not notice, and you can turn off the TV speakers if there is no one trying to listen without headphones.These were all minor annoyances, and overall we are glad to have the unit.  I advised my mom, who is 87, to ignore the volume controls on the headphones and just use the TV remote to adjust volume.  And the balance control really only has to be set once.
