VI have been using the Sony RF-985R wireless headphones up till I picked up these Rs-180.  I found the two are totally the opposite in many ways. The Sony are the most comfortable for wearing for extended periods while the 180's are not so comfortable after wearing for even an hour or two.I found the diameter to be too narrow around the ears and they place too much pressure on the side of the head. While the Sony's are  many times more comfortable with their large foam ear pads and head band.  The Sony's provided a rather dull sound field while the 180's are much better.. ..almost outstanding.  The Sony's have a reasonably easy to use volume & on off switch while the 180's are so poorly designed ergonomically -- that you have to remove them from your head to adjust them to either turn on or off or adj the volume.  So neither set warrants a high rating.  Like some of the others posts, one fix for the 180 is to glue on some sort of raised button so you can find the vol up and down ..  I detest having to remove the 180's from the head to simply raise or lower the vol.  The only reason I dont give them one star is they do provide excellent audio response.  Personally,  I think they should re-design the 180 ergonomically ASAP.  Then they might get five stars.. Something else better on the 180's is the range is over twice as far as the Sony's.  So neither one is the perfect wireless headset.  I plan to try gluing on some sort of reference nib on the vol controls to fix it but a user shouldn't have to modify such a product.  So thats why I give them 3 stars. one neg for the uncomfortable head band ear pads and another neg for the poor vol controls.
