sg3
VNot the total solution for me
p1199
sg5
VI took my time listening to these headphones under many conditions before choosing to write a review. I think I've done my duty on that now and I am ready to say my part. To begin with, I will state that this review is based on connecting these headphones to the headphone jack of a Denon AVR-2311CI.IF you are buying these headphones for musical interests alone, you may be pretty satisfied - for the most part. The dynamic range is quite acceptable - bass, mid, and treble are fairly represented. I experienced some wireless drop-out 15ft on the other side of an exterior wall and 35ft through one interior wall, but all-in-all, I was satisfied. Note that there are no other RF signals (the signal this unit uses) generated within my home that I am aware of that might cause such a conflict that would affect the range.The greatest disappointment came with signals that varied rapidly from low to high in all dynamic ways - satellite audio, and in particular live events therein. There were pops, crackles, and rattles every time I turned around. Apparently, a dynamic volume adjustment algorithm then triggers a volume decrease in an attempt to address this. This would seem to me to be an attempt at signal processing within this unit that fails in some unexpected circumstances and creates a rather nasty experience. Pop, crack, volume down - volume rises in a bit until the next crackle, then down again. It's like it's choking on the signal.The only way I could mitigate this behavior was to turn the receiver's volume below -23DB. This may also work for some, but be aware that there will be a loss of quality regardless as the circuitry in the unit is always trying to compensate and you will start to detect a sort of hiss in place of the pops and crackles as the unit continues to try and boost the volume. Since these headphones are open, the volume isn't high enough at this level to blot out external noises. If only the RS-180 could be ignorant and let you manually adjust the settings to your own satisfaction. In short, it needs a purely "manual" mode.If you expect to be fairly close to the base and are listening to audio sources that are consistent in their dynamic ranges, such as CD or DVD, you might be golden. If you are outside of the ranges in distance I noted, you may experience occasional drop-out; if you are listening to sources that may change their dynamic ranges or volume levels rapidly, such as satellite/cable sources, adjustments made to the audio signals by the circuitry of this product might create "artifacts" that will disappoint you in the least - or maybe render the product unacceptable to you.All this would have yielded 3 (really, 2.5) stars.But wait - there's more. I don't like the fact that when this unit connects the base to the headset that it fails to extinguish the LED on the base - it flashes relentlessly. I also dislike the fact that when you finally find the obtusely positioned on/off button on the headset to turn it off that the base then continues to flash furiously. Is this a by-product of supporting multi-headsets? Surely they could have done something else. Turn out the lights.And may the force help you if, for "sanitary" purposes (reading your product manual), you need to replace these earpad covers - they are quite specialized in construction, as they snap and twist on. Expect to pay at the least $50, likely more - if you can find them. I did find a UK source, none in the USA at this time. If your ears get sweaty, your time will come.These additional issues take this unit down to 2 stars... would have given 1 1/2, but that is not available. Premium price, not premium design or performance for general usage. The RS-180 may suit audiophiles that are happy with the range limitations. Mileage may vary for other users working with varied audio sources and applications.UPDATE: The ALC is not active and never has been. Not sure why most who would spend the $$$ on this model would need it.
