VAwesome sound, poor design
p1205
sg5
VThis is an odd product to review for me, because the product absolutely excels in their area of sound delivery over a wireless connection.  In fact, it is so much better than anything else I've ever tried, it's almost not in the same ball park, but the headphone design is relatively poor compared to the cheaper competition.  (otherwise 5 stars no question.)The great:Sound quality is better than anything else I've heard in a wireless setup.The battery lasts for many, many hours before the headphones need to be recharged (of course YMMV) but I can leave them off the charging station for weeks on end without them running out of power, where other brands would need to charge at least once a week under similar viewing conditions.The headphones are comfortable, breathe well, and provide excellent sound from low, mid to high.It's really nice to not need to be in line of sight of the transmitter and still hear what's being said.  Depending on the show, I might pop into the kitchen to make something, swing downstairs, walk outside to get the mail, and the sound continues no problem.  I've gone at least 100 yards away from the base and haven't lost audio quality.It's pretty easy to set up dual headphones on the same transmitter, which is nice if you and your spouse want to watch a loud/scary movie and the kids are in bed.The bad:For expensive headphones, they have some of the stupidest design choices I can imagine.1.  The volume buttons are tiny, and physically adjacent (on opposite sides) to the power button.  Try to turn it up by pressing the "+" button, and if you're off my a millimeter they turn off instead.  It's not easy to see anything on these buttons, so to adjust the sound you basically need to take them off of your head.2.  While the transmitter will turn off after about 10 minutes if no headphones are on, if the headphones and transmitter are both left on, and the TV etc. are turned off, both devices will stay on forever.  Headphones are not smart enough to turn off on their own.  Most wireless headphones I've owned know to power off after X minutes of no sound input.3.  When the unit is running low on power, the green light on the side of the unit will flash faster, rather than some sort of audible warning.  It would be nice if the low power warning were something you could hear, rather than something you can't really see when they're going to run out of power.I had some really cheap wireless headphones in the past, which used a dial for volume/power (rotate the dial to turn the volume up, all the way down and *click* and they're off, easy to use while you're wearing them) and auto powered off, they were a quarter of the price, and yet so much better in that one area.So for me, 4 stars due to the stupid button setups, but if you care about sound, then 5 stars and you will be floored with the audio they deliver.After over 6 months of usage I still love them, and am very happy I bought them, even with the negatives to the product listed above.
