VThe good, the bad and the ugly.
p1975
sg5
VI purchased two complete sets of RS180s. Four previous wireless headphones sets I've owned transmitted in the 900mHz range and had the typical problems of constant hiss, dropouts and clicks. It was like having someone with a dog clicker right beside your ears. We use wireless headphones in the living room and the master bedroom so sometimes they even received audio from the wrong base.Perhaps past experience has heightened my expectations for such a premium-priced product. That said, I'll attempt to balance the good, the bad and the ugly.Pros:  * Great audio. Very dynamic with good voice definition.  * Good range compared to previous 900mHz headphones. I haven't found a single dead spot in the house.  * Comfortable cuffs that keep extraneous sounds out and the headphone audio in.  * Multiple sets of headphones can be used in the same home at the same time without interference or crosstalk.  * Headphones from different sets can be manually reassociated so they work on the same base at the same time.Cons:  * Both the headphones AND THE BASE shut off when the headphones are placed on the charging cradle or if the headphones are shut off for about 5 minutes. Neither one powers on automatically. Other headphones (at a fraction of the cost) turn on as soon as the headband expands from being placed on the head. No button pushing. Simple. Elegant. This is a major shortcoming. Nothing has required me to physically go to the entertainment center to turn it on for at least 30 years. What were they thinking?  * The pushbutton controls on the headphones are too small and too close together for reliable use by touch alone. The combination mute/power button is placed between the volume up/down buttons so missing it is a challenge when a single finger tip can easily press all three buttons at the same time.  * All controls and markings on the base are tiny and don't contrast with the base color so are virtually illegible.  * One's ears may get hot after awhile simply because the cuffs do fit so well.  * The "multifunction button" backlight flashes constantly as well as an LED on the headphones. I can see having them flash during base to headphone association but once that's successful the flashing in a darkened room is just annoying.  * There's no printed owner's manual included. You have to print your own from the enclosed DVD or from an online download. Not including the manual at this product's price point is inexcusable.The worst part is there was a 50% failure rate. Someone else submitted a review noting that he could not get the headphones to work farther than 3' from the base. One set of mine worked fine for a day and a half and then did exactly that. With two complete sets I could associate both headphones with each transmitter base. Sure enough, both headphones worked with one base but neither worked more than 2' away from the other base. A call to Sennheiser support confirmed that the base had failed. Amazon replaced the failed set since it was only 3 days old. Hopefully, this won't be a recurring problem.I'm going to risk keeping both sets only because the audio clarity is so much better. The constant dropouts and clicks from the old 900mHz sets were infuriating.
p1976
sg7
VTheCheezWhiz
p1977
sg9
VVerified Purchase
p1978
