F4.0
sg3
VThe Best Solution for Apartment Living
p1981
sg5
VA neighbor complained about my surround system to my apartment management complex. The subwoofer was driving them nuts, as it would me. I thought I was destined to go back to regular TV audio (which is lousy these days). I like movies and I like to hear the effects, so I was really disappointed when I thought my relaxation hobby would come to an end as my Sony Bravia has less than adequate audio speakers.I started to research headphones as a solution. I never considered wireless an option. Wireless? Really?  The more I researched on line, and talked to folks at electronic stores, Sennheiser was the one constant suggestion. Skeptically, I purchased the RS 180 system. Problem solved.They transmit sound quite well (not quite as potent as a good surround system, but I will say I hear voice/speech better with headphones, just by their very nature). They offer freedom to roam about, obviously, because there's no cord. They are easy to set up and operate, for the most part. And I often forget I'm wearing them. They have actually become the preferred way I watch TV (and listen to my iTunes) in my apartment because they offer such clear audio and I don't have to worry about disrupting others.I keep the unit out of sight; behind the TV. There's no interference. There's no hiss while in operation. There's no frequency to have to find. Plug and play, basically. There is a speech intelligibility button the on the base which I leave turned on; it seems to give the audio a bit of a boost. I'm not exactly sure why I'd want to keep it turned off and the instructions don't offer much of an explanation, other than "when turned on, this seems to make voice intelligibility better." So, what's the point? Who isn't going to want to hear their audio?! It's a bit confusing.The only real downside is what many reviews mention: The audio controls on the headphones themselves are difficult to manage without taking them off. And the L/R balance buttons are a little strange but they are meant for folks with hearing difficulties so I can appreciate them, even though they are annoying when accidentally touched. Again, all of the function buttons are difficult to adjust while wearing the headphones. I have to take them off to adjust volume, for example, leaving me to guess at  adjustment levels before putting them back on; and I miss some audio this way. It's not a deal breaker by any means. I do think the developers would be wise to find a solution to the operational control functions in their next generation.Bottom line: An EXCELLENT solution if you live in an apartment and wish for better audio from your TV but don't wish to disturb neighbors with a surround system. Or, if you live in a house where others don't want to hear your audio, etc. The technology is very satisfying; more than I ever would have guessed.
