VSennheisers ROCK!!
p1987
sg5
VI've had three different wireless headphones over the past decade-plus and none have sounded as superb as the Sennheiser RS 180. The only slight knock I have is that the range isn't as good as I'd hoped it would be. I can walk around the entire top floor of my house and the sound is absolutely PERFECT. If I go downstairs, about 90% of the downstairs is covered; there's a slight dead-zone in the garage. The problem becomes most prevalent when I go outside while mowing or working around the outside of the house. There are certain dead spots around the property where the sound will just drop out and then come back as I move around. I'll try moving the transmitter closer to the outside and see if that clears the problem, but it's really not that much of an issue.I almost thought I had a problem, at one point. I'm studying Chinese and the lessons have pauses while it waits for your response. I heard the usual question about how to say something and then - total, complete silence. I mean DEAD silence. Not a single, solitary sound. No subtle hiss, static or anything else. I can't emphasize how disconcerting it was to hear (not hear??) such silence. I thought something had gone wrong because when I'm wearing the earbuds and listening to my iPod Touch, the silence isn't as total and complete. As I started to worry that something had gone wrong the lesson continued. The sound is so clear, it's wonderful. I later changed over to listening to Norah Jones and I heard subtle sounds from the instruments that I'd never heard before, even while listening over external speakers connected to my laptop. I do have a bit of a complaint about the placement of the switches on the side of the right earcup. The volume and on/off buttons are in a strip roughly one inch long and about a quarter of an inch wide. You have three buttons: up-volume, on/off, down-volume. Invariably, I end up turning off the unit when I'm trying to raise or lower the volume. It's not particularly cold now, but I expect that I'm going to have a problem discerning which is which when my fingers are frozen as I rake mountains of snow off the solar panels on my roof. It's not a big deal, just something to be aware of. I would've designed it differently, but I'm certainly not regretting my purchase. I have to add that the left and right channel adjustments are there, also, but I don't really fool with the channels, so it wouldn't be an issue with me. Because of volume adjustment/on-off button placement and the range problem, I only gave it a four-star rating. Otherwise, I would give it a six-star, just for the sound quality, if that were possible.
