VI've been in search for good wireless headphones for years. I've finally found them and I'm impressed. I'm an audiophile on a budget. I listen to a lot of music, usually on my wired Sennheiser HD595s. I've been really happy with them and sold on Sennheiser's quality. These are almost as good as the wired HD595 cans. So good in fact that I will probably only use the wired headphones for mixing/monitoring. I would give the RS180 a solid B+ in terms of sound quality, which is as good as it gets for wireless so far (I'm excited about the RS220 coming next year). The range on these is amazing. I have a bunch of wireless devices around the transmitter, two wireless keyboard/mouse adapters, bluetooth, and a wireless router (using both 2.4 and 5 for N). I was able to walk all around my house without these cutting out. I was even able to go outside well into the back yard with only a couple drop outs. I purchased an addition set of HDR 180 to pair with the RS 180 transmitter. It was very easy and now I have two sets working perfectly for those times when I want to watch a movie with another person late at night.A lot of people complain about the location of the buttons on the right headphone, but it took me all but 2 minutes to get used to it. I was walking around the house adjusting the volume without a problem. This issue is a non-issue for me.SO to sum it up, these have excellent range and the best sound quality that I've heard on wireless headphones by far. If you're thinking about purchasing...don't delay. You won't be disappointed. I usually don't write reviews, but these really impressed me.EDIT: These were so good that I purchased another set for the living room. For those who are curious, you can run two transmitters simultaneously without any interference between the two. Also, even with two separate transmitters, I still don't get any interference with my WiFi.
