VSennheiser RS, HDR 180: good performance - medicre build and poor ergonomics
p2011
sg5
VThe Sennheiser HDR 180 has been well-received and reviewed and that's why I bought my pair. The overall sound is very good and so I have no complaints about that.  However, though the apparent line-of-sight range will not be a factor for the average home, intervening walls and corners will - so if you wonder behind a couple of walls and/or corners you will lose your sound. If you plan to work in the garage while your RS 180 is in the living room you are not going to be pleased.What I must severely criticize is the dunderheaded ergonomic stupidity evinced by - not the engineers - but stylists and industrial designers. They had to get their fat, untalented little fingers on the cosmetics and general design/appearance of the headphones; it would have been far, far better had the same guys who designed the RS 120 been called upon to design the RS, HDR 180. In a nutshell: all the headset's controls are on the right earpiece - aligned in a row -without hardly any space between buttons. The volume control buttons are separated by a "multifunction" button - all flush one to the other, followed by (with but a slight space) L-R balance buttons. All work as you would want them to, but you have to take the phones off your noggin to look at what button you are activating and then put the phones back on to check the results; it really helps if you have Lilliputian fingers. I have no doubt that with enough practice one will be able to do this with pure feel - but why go through a frustrating, time consuming training process? Also, as is done on the RS 120, why not place some controls on the otherwise barren left earpiece and why not give each button ample space separation and a distinctive shape?There are a total of four LEDs - the important one being the red LED which tells you the base unit is charging. There are two others on the base unit and another on the headset which of course can't see when wearing the headset.  Steady and flashing LEDs, as well as the interval between flashes have different meanings and one has to look these up in the owner's manual - I refuse to commit them to memory. The utility of the foregoing LED messages is extremely limited and borders on the useless - other than for the charging and signal lights.The construction is nicely executed but all plastic; the headband really calls for spring steel but it too is plastic.  Each ear pad is held in place to its respective ear cup by two small plastic ears which have to align perfectly with matching holes. In each cup resides a rechargeable battery. If you drop the headset on a hard floor there is a high probability at least one ear pad will come loose and allow the retained battery to fly away to a no doubt hard-to-access place. How much shock and physical stress those little plastic ears will take remains to be seen. A better, foolproof, choice would have been to use Velcro tape to hold ear cup to ear pad. I may have to do that if the plastic ears break.All-in-all, I am pleased with the performance of the HDR 180 but the build quality and ergonomics are far less than remarkable.
