sg3
VWere it not for the lag and hissing...
p2017
sg5
VThe Sennheiser RS 180 is Sennheiser's top US wireless headphone setup; and, with what Sennheiser usually delivers, I expected more.The PhonesThe phones are Sennheiser's usual top notch construction: the plastic is solid, the joints are dependable, the velour padding is immensely comfortable, and the weight is acceptable. The operating buttons on the right-hand phone, however, leave much to be desired. The buttons are flat and depress shallowly, leaving for difficult button-pressing. The power button is, oddly, between the volume buttons, leading to some referencing each time volume or power is to be accessed. Furthermore, the volume controls are on the phones exclusively and consist of  holding, not  pressing. Several attempts at discovering the change in level resulted in these findings: pressing the button rapidly results in no change of level while holding the button results in a constant change in level; therefore, to achieve an exact level which is not the highest or lowest, careful half-second-presses are required for meaningful measurement. The battery life of the included AAA rechargable batteries is respectable (16-24 hrs), though the time is diminished as volume increases. Even with the long life, though, the recommended recharge time of 16 hours is unacceptable. Users report that recharging can finish in 8 hours, though reports are mixed. No rechargable device that is conceivable for everyday use should need to charge for longer than an average night's sleep.The TransmitterThe transmitter, too, is top notch in construction: it's light because it's plastic, but it sits firm and looks good on a desk, with unobtrusive LEDs which indicate transmission (about one flicker per 5 seconds in sync with the phones) and a dim charge light which goes out when the phones have finished charging. The audio cable from source to transmitter is a gold-plated, good-feeling mini stereo jack on both ends while the AC has an international, exchangable head design with US, European, and Asian prongs included. While this is probably not intended for travelling convenience, it could prove useful to a select few.The SoundEven with the usual, Sennheiser construction, despite being marred by some thoughtless design choices, the sound that comes out of these has two big problems: lag and hissing. First, while we expect wireless headphones to be slower than wired headphones, users shouldn't be noticing this difference in movies, TV, and games. While this doesn't affect music or other non-visual media, visual use will suffer: expect .1 to .2 second lag even if the transmitter is within inches of the receiving phones. The result is a movie, show, or game that is visually ahead of its audio; expect lips, frenetic action, and aural cues to all be off. While users might grow accustomed to the lag, a price tag like this one shouldn't ask them to. Second, while reviewers here and abroad have raved about the lack of hissing, popping, and static, expect some. If the phones are near their max volume, the speakers will produce unacceptable levels of static to the point of hissing. The source volume affects this less, but silent sources are met with audible static regardless of acceptable source levels. Popping, too, can occur, though not to an excessive degree. Again, despite being wireless, users should receive what was promised for this price tag: inaudible hissing, popping, and static at all but the highest volumes and no noticable lag in audio.Until Sennheiser demonstrates that their wireless solutions can match the performance of their wired ones, I'll be sticking with the Sennheiser HD555 Professional Headphones with Sound Channeling.
