VVery good sound, but terrible usability details make them frustrating
p2023
sg5
VI bought these as an upgrade from some very nice Sony IR wireless headphones that lacked in audio quality and range that were about the same price as these headphones 6 yrs ago when I got them.These headphones are a huge sonic upgrade.  I love the sound quality, I love that it's RF and I can walk into another room.  The stand is fair, the headphones are reasonably comfortable.  There is a lineout on the back of the stand so that these headphones can sit between your source and another device--for me, these are plugged into a computer and I have some cheap speakers downstream.  It's nice not to have to re-cable or adjust things to change the sound output.  Previously I was using a rackmount headphone amp to serve a similar purpose.I also own Sennheiser noise canceling headphones and the top-of-the-line HD 800s.  I really like Sennheiser headphones.However, where these fall hugely short is usability.  First, there's two power buttons, one on the headphones and one on the stand.  This is ridiculous--the Sony headphones these replaced had 0 power buttons.  Lifting the headphones off the stand should turn on both the stand and the headphones.  The user doesn't should have to do both.  The Sony headphones also had an ingenious on/off built into the band of the headphones that would conserve battery life by turning off the headphones when they were not on my head.  I'm sure Sony has patented this but Sennhesier needs to figure out something similar.So when I want to use these headphones, it takes me several attempts at hitting buttons to get things on and going.  It's frustrating and it's distracting.  There is a light on the headphones that flashes when the power is turning on/off, but unlike, say, my Plantronics bluetooth ear bud, it doesn't change colors for on/off, so I never know if I am turning it on or off.  I can't tell from the base either.  The headphones come with a complex grid of LED blink rates and what they all mean, but who has time to sit down with a headphone manual?Great sound and so I keep them, but the usability sucks really bad.  I might try the newer Sony models at some point.
