VGreat sound, annoying to use.
p2149
sg5
VI have the HDR160 set, and while the sound quality is great, using them can be very irritating which is why I am considering the RS180. Unfortunately the RS180 seems to have the same poor design that made me come to dislike my HDR set enough to want to replace them.Instead of using separate led's or color states, the status of the headset is determined by a single green led that seems to flash randomly, if at all. You are expected to memorize a timing chart and then count pulses within the timeframe of a second, and be able to differentiate those between pulses that occur within the span of 5 seconds in order to tell how the headset is operating. Not exactly intuitive.The ritual of having to keep the power pressed on the base station, then doing the same for the set, gets tiresome since the base station does not automatically power on and wait to sync the headset as soon as there is an audio signal. It is happy to turn itself off, though, even though it is connected to wall power. Hold and wait. Hold and wait. Was that long enough? How many blinks was that? Is it syncing? Is that low battery? Is it on mute? The indicator is next to useless.These sets seem designed for an android with a built in chronometer and endless patience. Morse code operators might like them too.
